animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Sadie (SC) is a female Black Mouth Cur mix rescued in South Carolina. Sadie was born on December 3, 2020. She is good with people of all ages and other dogs. Sadie's Momma is a Black Mouth Cur mix, but we never knew Sadie's Dad, so we can't be sure what Sadie's actual breed mix is. Sadie found herself stuck in a kill shelter with her Momma and siblings. A shelter is a dangerous place for a young puppy, and it was likely that Sadie wouldn't make it out alive. So as soon as we received a plea to help Sadie, we of course said YES! and Sadie was on her way to happiness. If you're looking for puppy love, and the more puppy kisses the better, Sadie is your girl! Please apply online to adopt Sadie (SC) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

animal.description:
Hi meet Emi, 

Emi is a lovely 7 years old Queensland Mix. She is an adorable, joyful dog that likes to snuggle. She loves going out on adventures with her humans. She is sweet and playful. She would like a home that will take her on adventures and give her lots of love. As nice as Emi is she needs to be in a home as an only dog, with no other dog socialization. 

Emi is an owner surrender but by no fault of her own.

We hold an event every weekend at our facility on SATURDAY 11-5pm.   Please visit our social media platforms for the specifics for each weekend as it changes from week to week. Please find our application at lovejoyfoundation.org when you come to an event please bring that filled out in hand with you. You can find our application at Lovejoyfoundation.orgYou MUST submit an APPLICATION via email in hopes to get an appointment, our application is found on our website lovejoyfoundation.org. If you do not get a phone call by Friday then we did not have anything available for you or the pet of interest was adopted before we got you application. We are a Southern California based rescue and do nothing adopt further than an hour from our headquarters in Inglewood, Ca. we do not adopt out more than a 30 minute radius. We appreciate you being understanding and Patient as we attempt to go back to a new normal.

animal.description:
Our senior boy, Caddo, has made so much progress since being abandoned in that outdoor shelter near Shreveport. 

Now to help him find the perfect family to finish out his golden years. Caddo was unable to walk when he came to us last month. But, he is already showing huge progress on his medication. Imagine how well he will do with a little more time for the supplements and food to kick in!  

Want to bring him this happy love buy home?  Visit Canerossorescue.org to apply. 

Want to send him a gift?  He would love some joint supplements or all things cozy. The joint supplements are making a huge difference, and we would love to send him to his adopter with a couple months worth of them. 

Chewy https://www.chewy.com/g/cane-rosso-rescue_b71822833
Amazon:  https://a.co/dQnhFLM

Thanks for considering a Cane Rosso Rescue dog! 
We place dogs mostly in Texas but have adopted out a few out-of-state as well.
 
If you are interested in one of our dogs, please first complete our adoption application.
You can find it at https://www.canerossorescue.org/adoption-application . His adoption fee is $150 plus tax. Our dogs are spayed or neutered, microchipped, vaccinated and heartworm tested and treated (if tested positive) before going to a new home. For more information, visit our website www.canerossorescue.org
or email us at rescue@canerosso.com.

animal.description:
Judy is a slap-happy 4-year-old pupster who's willing to join you on ALL your adventures!

This lowrider pittie is as sweet and playful as they come. She'll need an active family to keep up with her, since she loves to run and play! 

We saved Judy from the shelter and brought her out to our trainer so that she could be assessed and learn leash manners. The trainer says she's a well-behaved, curious girl who loves walks and runs in the park, and plenty of belly rubs!

Judy was tested in the shelter's play yard with another calm dog and did fine, but our trainer will do a full assessment to determine the temperament of dogs that she prefers. 

Judy is house-trained, crate-trained, and weighs 65 lbs. She enjoys car rides and would love to accompany you on errands!  She would do best in a single-family home with a backyard so she has room to poke around and play.

animal.description: Doyle is a little doll! He is so friendly and has never met a person or dog that he doesn't like. animal.description:
Axel is a 4-year-old, 70 lb, bulldog mix looking for his forever family. He is UTD, neutered, housebroken, crate trained, and is learning to walk on leash. Axel is high energy and would love a family to go on adventures with. He is good with dogs, not good with cats, and good with kids. Axel does not like going to the vet (who does?!) and needs proper muzzle training/sedation to safely take him to the vet. 

Axel has to find my new forever home because the current owner is experiencing health issues and cannot also care for Axel.

Adoption requirements are as such:


	Large breed experince 
	Not a first time dog parent 


Please note, Axel is part of Happy Trails Animal Rescues rehoming program. She has not been tested or evaluated and the information gathered is from the current owners personal statements regarding health and temperament. The owner is subject to placement outside of our organization. We cannot guarantee availability.

animal.description:
Meet Mavi! 
Mavi is just a little ray of sunshine wherever she goes! such a happy girl and her smile is infectious. 
Mavi has spent time with our "Halo kids" and has proven to us that she loves kids - she's gentle and respectful with them. Mavi also enjoys play groups with other dogs that are smaller then her; dogs that are larger than her make her nervous and wouldn't be a goof fit. She does LOVE puppies! We aren't sure about cats but her friendly nature with little fluffy dogs leads us to believe she could possibly be ok - we can further test her if the need arises. Mavi is always down for a good snuggle on the couch and might possibly be defined as a couch potato. 
If you would like to learn more about Mavi, please fill out an application and we would love to schedule a Meet & Greet! 

Staff Highlights: 

Whitney: "I love how she loves kids. She is gentle and kind."
Courtney: "Love how gentle and motherly she is to the puppies."
Wendy: "She loves attention and will snuggle with you."
Regina: "She has never met a stranger!"

animal.description:
Molly is a playful 6ish year old German shepherd who loves food and belly rubs. She likes playing with dog toys but has never chewed anything she shouldn’t. She is house trained and doesn’t bark. She is great with older kids and is very loyal.   She’s happy going for walks, taking rides in the car or laying around being a couch potato.

She tolerates her foster dog-brother but doesn’t love him. She has not been around any other dogs or cats in our home.  She’s okay being in a crate on her own terms but doesn’t appreciate when we close the door. 
She sleeps with her tongue out. ?.

Molly came to us in very poor conditions.  She has received her last heartworm injection on December 30th.  She needs to stay chilled out for 6 weeks(until Feb 10th) and then she can go back to being a normal dog.  
   Molly can be adopted now to a quiet home or if it is a more active home she can be adopted after February 10th.   She will live a perfectly normal and happy life after that. She will be required to be on heartworm prevention for the rest of her life, as all dogs should be anyway. 
   Molly is $175.  She is spayed and up to date on vet care. We are looking for her forever home.   
  If interested we will need you to fill out an application and then we will get you in touch with the foster home, who knows her best!   
  She is being fostered in Excelsior Springs Mo.

animal.description:
Scout is a 4-ish years, 10-pound neutered male terrier mix, with pearly white teeth! He was unadoptable at the ACC due to behavioral issues and Waggytail scooped him up and placed him into a top-notch, 5 week Board & Train Program with ClarityK9.com (check him out on their fantastic Instagram stories https://www.instagram.com/clarity.k9/). Scout is now crate trained, housebroken, with good manners, basic obedience, tolerates cats and other dogs and is terrific on leash during his walks. Scout's training is a work in progress and we are looking for a dedicated person(s) who will agree to book Scout's trainer for several sessions in order to fully transfer and lock in his good behavior. Consistency is key to keeping Scout on track for a chance at a long and have a happy life, in a loving forever home, where he will reach new heights in his journey to becoming a perfect play buddy. Scout's adopter(s) will be taught to safely play fetch and tug with him, which he loves! In order to keep Scout's newly acquired good manners intact, he must be crated at night and is not allowed on human furniture. He needs a disciplined owner who will agree to follow a consistent routine of hand-feeding while continuing his obedience training. If you think you have the time and energy to continue Scout's journey from naughty to nice, and you are located in or near Brooklyn, Queens or Manhattan, please fill out an adoption application. 

Scout needs to be an only dog with no small children in the home. 

Please confirm in your adoption application that you agree to retain and work with Scout's current trainer. Tell us a little bit about your interest in learning how to continue his training routines.

Vaccinated for rabies, DA2PP, and bordetella. Neutered, microchipped, and heartworm negative. 

Please contact us DIRECTLY using the instructions below if you are interested in adopting one of our Waggytails! Visit our website (www.waggytailrescue.org) for an adoption application. It is important to fill out an application as soon as possible for consideration, and we require a complete application for you to meet an animal. 

Adoptions: waggyadopt@gmail.com

Waggytail Rescue CANNOT guarantee the exact age of any adoptable dog, or final size of any of our adoptable puppies. We rely on the information provided to us by veterinarians, shelters, owner surrenders and other circumstances bringing the dog into our rescue.

I'm a very happy boy and I love to follow my foster momma all around the house. She says I look like a manatee with a possum tail (bc I'm husky and I've lost a little bit of fur back there). I think she means to say that I am very handsome!

I get along fine with the other dogs in my foster home and even the cat! I also enjoy getting massages. If I'm standing, I will lean in to you as if to say, "more please!"

I am house-trained, crate-trained, know commands like "stay", "come", "sit", and "in" (my crate). I'm an all-around great catch! Will you be my forever?

My adoption fee is $175. I am up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, heartworm tested, neutered, and microchipped.
All of our dogs are spayed or neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped and if over 6 months of age, heartworm tested and on heartworm preventative in their foster home.

We require an approved application to meet any of our dogs. We do not have a shelter location and will not arrange a meeting without an approved application.

We strive to make sure the bios provided for our dogs are complete and accurate; we do understand that mistakes happen, however, so if you absolutely cannot find the answer to your question in the dog's bio, you can contact us for more information.

We require a home visit for each dog we adopt out, so we adopt within a 2 hour radius of Dayton, OH. If you are outside of this radius, we encourage you to contact your local rescue or shelter.

animal.description:
Daphne came into a rural shelter and was not claimed by her owner so we took her in. She is a small, 5-6 year old beagle. 

When Daphne arrived she was full of intestinal worms and underweight and really didn't feel great so we didn't get to know her true personality. Now that she has been treated for the worms and putting on weight she is coming out of her shell. She is a snuggler with her foster mom. She is not afraid of adults or children. She does like other dogs but doesn't like them getting right up in her face. She doesn't live with another dog so we don't know if she would resource guard food or toys at this time. 

She is OK in a crate, doing well with housebreaking and leash walking.

She is scheduled to be spayed January 28th. She did test positive for heartworms so we started her on the Doxycycline and the monthly heartworm preventive. She will receive her vaccinations and micro-chipping when she is spayed, and then she will be ready for her forever home.

If interested in Daphne our application can be found at www.homesfurhounds.com. She is located in Williamsburg.

Medical Notes:
-I am heartworm positive. I will need to be treated with 28 days of doxycycline (an inexpensive antibiotic) before I receive my heartworm injections. You can still adopt me, but the cost of the treatment will become your responsibility, ODHS always recommends you contact a vet to price this treatment if you are interested in adopting me beforehand.
-I am Ehrlichia and Lyme positive. Treatment is 28 days of doxcycyline (an inexpensive antibiotic). The adopter is responsible for treatment of the dog. ODHS does not pay for this treatment. 

Hi my name is Patriot! I’m 2 years old and about 44 lbs! I’m still learning about walking on my leash, but I love car rides, cuddles, and humans who give me love and attention. I do well in my crate when my foster is at work and I play well with the resident dogs.

You can come adopt me or even join our foster program to help the humans learn all the awesome things about new dogs like me! Learn more on our website! 

Hope to see you soon! 

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

Educational articles:
3/3/3 Rule;
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards.

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturdays. 
Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer 

Note: ODHS only adopts to Virginia and surrounding states (including D.C.). A $50 out of state fee applies.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email US at barbarak@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Marshall
Estimated Breed : Pointer Mix
Approximate Age: 1 year
Approximate Weight: approx. 48 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Marshall is an energetic, happy boy looking for a forever home. He loves kids and other dogs, and loves to play in the yard. Because of his energy level, an apartment will not suit him. Will you give Marshall a loving home and family to call his own?
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
All of our foster dogs are kept in individual homes. Go to our website Bayareasiberian.org to get the foster home contact if you do not see it in the bio.Hi, I'm Rex! I'm an one year old Husky mix who'll steal your heart at first sight with my dazzling blue eyes and snow white coat. I'm both potty and crate trained, and respond pretty well to basic obedience commands-"sit", "come", "paw". You'll find that I'm a perfect companion! On those chilling days, I'll bright your mornings with sweet little kisses, and patiently wait for the opportunity to seat by your side and cuddle. And if you're up for an adventure, I bring plenty of energy-but nothing out of the extraordinary for a pup at my age that can't be easily managed with regular exercise. You can count on me to go on long walks, hiking trips or any other outdoor activities-sniffing is my thing! Love belly rubs, playing with other dogs, and chewing my bone. I don't bark, guard my toys or food, nor growl or give a stink eye. If you already have another dog, rest assure that I'll be a good brother.

Just ask you to please be a bit patient and consistent with me as I can be stubborn sometimes and don't respond to commands right away (sorry, it's in my nature!). I get anxious when I'm alone by myself, and tend to gulp my food as fast as I can, but those are all littles things that I learned after spending too much time at the shelter. Your love will help me make those insecurity traits go away in a heart beat! Go to BAYAREASIBERIAN.org for contact information on the foster dog.

I do good with other dogs, I just need them to give me my space if they are around so I do not extend my injury further. animal.description:
Meet Bailey!

Bailey is ready to find her forever home. Baily is around 11 (but young at heart) and weighs 40 lbs. She is spayed, micro-chipped, vaccinated and heartworm negative. She is good with other respectful dogs. She is a little too interested in cats. She is crate trained and housebroken. We do not know Baileys breed(s). She sheds (wire top coat and soft undercoat), is vocal likes to talk to you and has some terrier tendencies but also some husky tendencies. 

Bailys ideal home would be with an owner who loves to go on walks and hikes. Bailey has great leash skills. She would love to have an owner who likes to work in their yard and garden. Bailey LOVES being outside. Baily is sweet. She likes things calm so no kids in the home. 

Bailey requires a home with a fenced yard (chain link, wrought iron or privacy fencing). Rock walls or tree lines are not acceptable forms of fencing. Invisible (electric) fencing is not acceptable. We do not adopt out to homes with invisible (electric) fences. Applications received that do not meet our fencing guidelines will not be considered.

Potential adopters must be over the age of 25 and live within a 25-mile radius of Peachtree City, GA. Other locations will be considered on a case-by-case basis depending on the availability of a home visit.

Link to our adoption process (includes information on fees):
https://houndsinpounds.com/process/

Link to our application:
https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24581/generic

animal.description:
Sweet Zeena is looking for her forever home! She is a 3yr old Chihuahua mix that weighs 10lbs and is full grown. Zeena came to us due to her owners not being able to care for her medically. After being in labor over 24 hours with a puppy stuck, she was surrendered to AZSDR where we rushed her to the emergency vet so she could have a C-section. She unfortunately lost all three of her puppies. AZSDR was quick to provide her with all the medical care she needed, and she has healed in a loving foster home. Now she is ready to find her forever home! Zeena's favorite activities are long walks and cuddling in her person's lap. This smart girl is potty trained, leash trained and enjoys rides in the car. Zeena likes to sleep in bed with her human. Zeena is learning to trust again and may be somewhat owner possessive. She is also chatty when she meets new people but is won over with pets and cuddles. Zeena is dog selective and needs to meet any other dogs in the home, preferably smaller quiet ones. She would also enjoy being the only spoiled doggie in the home.

Zeena has lived with cats before and has done well with them.

She is an escape artist and is known to dart through open doors so no apartments as she will keep running. Zeena also has some dermal cysts on her head which are not dangerous to her, the result of a dog attack three years ago but a vet was never seen for this until now. Zeena is the biggest sweetheart searching for a home where she can be safe and feel loved.

She is spayed and

up to date on vaccines, microchipped and vet checked. H

er

adoption fee of $

350

includes a

complimentary

vet visit.

Please email

kim@chemkim.com

for more information about adopting this sweetie.

For the safety of our staff and customers, we ask that you practice social distancing, sanitization, and if exposed to Covid-19 or sick to please stay home.--

animal.description:
These 9 week old Dane mix pups are pretty confident kiddos, although
they are definitely a little less so as individuals than as a group.  It will be important for them to continue their training and have opportunities to be social. 
They are all puppy - jumpy, happy and energetic.  
Some are a bit more timid than others but generally they are really into people, very eager for your attention.   They are just delightful and can settle down and like to cuddle some as individuals and sit quietly when you rub their
ears...very sweet. 

The adoption fee includes a training program that adopters will agree to participate in.  

Please complete an application on our website to set up an appointment to meet these little rascals.    www.adoptmountainpets.org

Adopters will be considered on the totality of the application and how it matches the particular pet's needs.

Most dogs who come from the shelter will not be house trained.

We do not know or make guarantees that a dog or cat will do well with all children, other animals or is house-trained.

We will need to talk to all of the adults in the home prior to making an appointment to visit with a pet. 

In most cases its necessary to to have family dogs come into meet your potential adoptee. Please be sure your dogs are spayed or neutered and current on vaccines (distemper - parvo and rabies) before bringing them for a meeting.

All dogs must be transported home in a travel crate to transport your new pup home safely.

Renters must provide a copy of a lease indicating pets are allowed or contact information for the landlord.


Second Chance is happy to have been providing stray, surrender, adoption, and our Community Outreach services throughout the COVID situation.   

All services are provided by appointment only.  Please do not visit the shelter without first making calling the shelter. 

For the safety of our community, staff and volunteers all visitors are required to wear masks and follow the posted social distancing processes *see below.  Do not make an appointment if you are not comfortable following these procedures.  Thank you for understanding and your support.  

If you are interested in meeting or adopting one of our pets or have questions about the process please see our website at www.adoptmountainpets.org or call the Shelter between 11:00 am and 5:45 pm Tuesday through Saturday. 970 626 2273

*  We want to provide you excellent customer service today and keep you and our team safe and healthy. Please read what we are asking you to do today to reduce the risk of spreading COVID-19:

• Maintain a distance of at least 6 feet from other people. Six feet is the average length of many dog leashes but handing a leashes to another person is not maintaining a six foot space.
• Follow staff instructions about how to drop off, pick up or meet a pet.
• If you have any symptoms of illness please reschedule.
• Wear a mask when interacting with staff
• Wash your hands or use hand sanitizer (you can find bottles throughout the property prior to interacting with staff, volunteers or pets.
• Once you have read these guidelines, please tell us you understand them and that you will follow them with at SCHS.
Thank you for your support, for adopting, for fostering and volunteering and understanding our need to do our part in stopping COVID – 19.

animal.description:
Meet Belarus!

UPDATE/Belarus has seen our amazing vet and after X Rays he determined that her leg is healing and she will have a full and complete recovery. She is taking medication and is prohibited from aerobic activity for 30 days while her leg continues to heal. She does not require crate rest and normal walking and activity is fine.

You are in for a treat with Belarus! This girl loves affection, treats, and you! A perfect day for her would be playing with the ball or learning a new trick. As long as it's with you, she will be happy!

Belarus ended up at a small rural shelter with an injured left front leg, this adorable and sweet girl was in pain and needed some help. The team at the shelter has no vet care available at the shelter so they reached out to rescue to help this cutie pie get the medical attention she needs and recover in a warm loving foster home. Her foster mom saw her worried face and knew she had to help.

Belarus is a fawn spayed female Shepherd mix that is 2 years old and weighs 39 pounds.

She is a sweet, affectionate, and playful girl that gets along with everyone, kids included, loves other dogs, and is nice to cats.

Belarus is looking for a loving family with home that can provide lots of snuggles and cuddles and some limited exercise and no aerobic activity for 30 days for her leg to continue to heal.

The leg doesn't slow her down one bit so she needs someone to lovingly monitor her activity and make sure she gets plenty of rest too!

She walks great on a leash and loves to go on car ride adventures, and sleeps with her favorite toy, frequently with all four feet in the air.

Belarus is crate and house trained.

If you think you might be the family where this little girl would fit right in forever on her road to recovery, please complete an application on our website and her foster mom will be in touch.

Belarus is spayed, UTD on vaccinations, Heartworm Negative and Micro Chipped.

Her leg treatment is covered by LHS.

Please apply at: http://legacyhumanesociety.org/adoptfoster/adoption-application/
We do not have a facility to house the dogs in our program. They are all kept in foster homes until they are adopted. Therefore, if you are interested in adopting from LHS, please complete an online application at http://legacyhumanesociety.org/adoptfoster/adoption-application/ and we will contact you asap about the status of your application.

animal.description:
Oh sweet, sweet Nelly! The first word that comes to mind for Nelly is PUPPY! She is a boxer/lab mix and is about 5 months old and weighs 40 lbs. Nelly is as friendly as can be. She's so excited when her people come home and gallops around like a baby horse. She loves snuggling up next to you or getting some scratches behind the ear. She is doing well with kennel training and sleeps through the night. Potty training is going great too, but she will appreciate your patience as she is young and still learning the rules. Nelly loves people and other dogs. We're not sure about kids or cats, but we guess that she'd do well. A fenced yard is required as she loves to run around and play. She is spayed and up to date on her shots. Nelly is ready to join your family and share her happy face with you everyday. Nelly
's adoption fee is $250. All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. This dog is fostered in Hays, KS and adopter must drive to pick up. We do not ship or deliver. We do allow out of state adoptions, however qualified in state applications will be given preference. Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. To learn about Hands of Hope Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at HandsofHopeRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
***Thank you for your interest in Magnificent Mutts and Meows. We hope everyone is saying safe during this challenging time. Due to the current regulations set forth by Governor Pritzker on group gatherings we will not be having adoption events until further notice. As an all foster based rescue this means that all meets will be by appointment only. Your whole family must be available to attend the meet as there will be no second meets scheduled to help limit contact between our team and the public. To help streamline the process please make sure your current pets are up to date, you have landlord/HOA approval, and that you are prepared to take the dog home with you immediately before submitting an application. Thank you & Please stay safe!***

Cynder just arrived from a network partner in the south with her litter of pups. Approximately 2-3years old and 45lbs. Since she just arrived we are still getting to know her. Cynder is very shy and nervous so she will need a patient owner who allow her to come around on her own time. Since she is so timid another dog in the home will give her more confidence and allow her to trust in people easier so her forever home should have another dog in it. Cats and kids are unknown at this time.

Check back for more information and possible restrictions once she fully settles into foster care.

If you are interested in adoption, please complete the Application to Adopt which you can find on our website (
www.magnificentmutts.org
) No phone calls please. Emails only.

Adoption Donation $300 (cash only)

Please visit www.magnificentmutts.org for the online dog or cat application.

Adoption Fees*

Adult cats starting at $125, Kittens starting at $165.
Dogs/Puppies starting at $225 minimum
Prices subject to change, please contact for specific adoption donations.

animal.description:
What’s better than a sweet old Bluetick Coon Hound? Bosley is one fine man weighing in at 90lbs! He is a lover of people and other dogs. He might steal your toy but we will never fight him for it! His favorite toy here is his teddy bear. Bosley has blastomycosis, a fungal disease that will take about three months to cure. He is also heartworm positive and will take about six month to rid of them. Since this sweet old man has a slow course of action for both heartworm and fungal disease, he will need to go to a home with a foster who is willing to keep up his treatments. After he is given a clean bill of health he will be able to be neutered. Heartworm and Blastomycosis are rarely transferred to other pets in the home as long as they are on proper prevention. Who wouldn’t want a big hunk-o-love like Bosley to keep them warm at night?

animal.description:
Well....I don't "Tango" as much as I use to....I enjoy the quieter life...you know napping, cuddles and all the attention I can get. My name is Tango and I am a 
neutered male Boxer about 7 yrs old and I weigh 62 lbs. I've been here several days and my owner hasn't come. I'll just go ahead and let you know I am heartworm positive.....I had all my toes crossed waiting on results to come back but....I feel pretty good though...no coughing or apparent health issues for now but it sure would be nice to find my forever home and someone who wouldn't mind helping me get treated. I'm a pretty sweet guy, quiet, laid back and get along well with other dogs. I'm just an older guy that needs a kind heart, a warm blanket and a family to call mine. If my owners don't come I will be available 1/26/21.  Adopting a dog from the Conway Animal Welfare Unit is a fairly easy process. The first step to adopting an animal is submitting an application. The application allows us to individually consider applicants and helps us to properly match our pets with new owners. We want to make sure that our pets are going to homes that are ready to provide for these pets long-term. Adoptions are $50 and this includes vaccinations, heartworm test, spay/neuter and microchip. As with any shelter animal, health is not guaranteed but we do our best to screen out those animals that are showing obvious signs of illness or disclose that information prior to adoption. All dogs are heartworm tested upon adoption. 

If you are interested in adopting a dog and you reside OUTSIDE the city limits of Conway and the dog is less than 12 wks old, the cost is $75 which includes a spay/neuter and micropchip. The spay and neuter can only be performed at Vilonia Vet Clinic or Companion Animal Spay/Neuter Clinic. If the animal is less that 12 wks and you live inside the city limits the adoption fee is $25 dollars and you receive a voucher for $120 to use at select clinics for spay/neuter. The other option is that you provide us with proof of a pre-paid spay or neuter at YOUR vet of choice.

animal.description:
Jon Boy was found as a stray in FW covered in scrapes, missing hair, and what appeared to be some small cysts or tumors. This 10 year old baby was absolutely terrified in the shelter. He his in the corner and was fearful of all the noises.  But, from the moment he left that shelter, he has been nothing but hugs, love, and an absolute doll. He has done great with other dogs, and is loving life with his foster. We are currently working on his skin and helping heal his leg. 

Jon Boy is going to make an AMAZING addition to someone’s family. He also has the cutest little trot you have ever seen. This is not a senior that is limping around. He is happy, loving, and is ready to spend his Golden years with a person looking to receive as much love as they are willing to give. 

Thanks for considering a Cane Rosso Rescue dog! 
We place dogs mostly in Texas but have adopted out a few out-of-state as well.

You can find it at https://www.canerossorescue.org/adoption-application . His adoption fee is $150 plus tax. Our dogs are spayed or neutered, microchipped, vaccinated and heartworm tested and treated (if tested positive) before going to a new home. For more information, visit our website www.canerossorescue.org
or email us at rescue@canerosso.com.

Meet Princess Fiona!!!  This sweet and loving girl is looking for her own castle to live in.  She wants to be the princess in her castle.  Fiona would love her own couch to sleep on and a pillow to rest her head on.  We have promised Fiona that we would find her the forever home she deserves.

She loves her people and loves to snuggle on the couch with them.  Fiona will get bursts of energy every so often, where she will do zoomies in the backyard.  They don't last very long, as she would prefer to nap in the sunshine.  She will do this in the backyard while you are gardening too.

Her first love is for people and only people!!!  She would do great as a family dog who has a fenced yard and does not have much interaction with other dogs.  She is a very smart girl who is willing to learn, so if you would like to bring her to training she will accept that for sure.  Let's find princess Fiona her forever home that she deserves to be the princess of the castle.

If you would like more information on Fiona, please contact
INFO.FETCHINGHEARTS@GMAIL.COM OR COPY LINK BELOW TO APPLY AND FILL OUT AN APPLICATION: https://www.fetchingheartsrescue.org/adoption-form-online to fill out an application.

Unless otherwise indicated, all dogs adopted through Fetching Hearts have received the following before being available for adoption:

Thorough veterinary examination

All routine annual vaccinations, including Rabies, DHLPP, Bordatella (Kennel Cough), Heartworm Test, Fecal Test, Deworming, Microchip, Flea and Tick Prevention and Heartworm Prevention.

Spay/Neuter
All dogs are quarantined for two weeks outside of the shelter (puppies four weeks) to ensure they don't break with disease.

VETTING NOTE: Fetching Hearts Rescue completely vets our dogs thoroughly to the best of our knowledge based on communication with our Southern Vets. If anything is brought to our attention, we treat the dog. After adopting the dog, you will be responsible for following up with all vetting going forward.

HEARTWORM NOTE: Dogs who were treated for Heartworm can test positive up to 4-6 months after last treatment. All dogs are immediately put on Heartguard/Ivermectin following the treatment to kill the Heartworm larvae. All dogs should be re-tested after 5-6 months from the last Heartworm treatment.

Hey friends! I'm Star, and my awesome personality outshines my name! I'm a 2 year old Am. Staff mix, I weigh 42 lbs. and I'm about as sweet as they come. I'm super wiggly and happy when I meet a friend, and I absolutely ADORE belly rubs!! I can be a little shy with strangers at first, but I warm up quickly and have lots of love to give! I'm friendly, playful, energetic, and I really love toys! I do fine with other dogs, and I'm good with the kiddos! If you're looking for a new addition to the family, a walking buddy, active playmate, couch potato...I can be all of the above! Come by & see me, I'm available now! Adopting a dog from the Conway Animal Welfare Unit is a fairly easy process. The first step to adopting an animal is submitting an application. The application allows us to individually consider applicants and helps us to properly match our pets with new owners. We want to make sure that our pets are going to homes that are ready to provide for these pets long-term. Adoptions are $50 and this includes vaccinations, heartworm test, spay/neuter and microchip. As with any shelter animal, health is not guaranteed but we do our best to screen out those animals that are showing obvious signs of illness or disclose that information prior to adoption. All dogs are heartworm tested upon adoption. 

If you are interested in adopting a dog and you reside OUTSIDE the city limits of Conway and the dog is less than 12 wks old, the cost is $75 which includes a spay/neuter and micropchip. The spay and neuter can only be performed at Vilonia Vet Clinic or Companion Animal Spay/Neuter Clinic. If the animal is less that 12 wks and you live inside the city limits the adoption fee is $25 dollars and you receive a voucher for $120 to use at select clinics for spay/neuter. The other option is that you provide us with proof of a pre-paid spay or neuter at YOUR vet of choice.

animal.description:
Rodney the rottie is an approx 2-3 yr old rottweiler mix with a natural tail and a giant smile.
He was recently found as a stray but nobody ever came for him, and we aren't sure why.  Rodney must have had a family not so long ago as he appears housebroken (although we would expect any dog going into a new home might have some accidents as they get adjusted), had a harness and leash on and seems to know some commands.
Rodney has tested well with other dogs but has been a little overexcited by them lately and would be best as your one and only.
Rodney's adoption fee includes his neutering, microchipping, age appropriate vaccinations and preventative vet care to date.

animal.description:
Happy has been in our system since October 2020! He came in very sick but after months of rehabilitation and a wonderful foster, Happy is now up for adoption. Happy got his name due to his really happy personality and how rapidly he wags his tail. Happy is an intelligent pup. He loves to sit and snuggle on the couch with a nice blanket and the tv. He enjoys his food with a little chicken broth. Happy likes Milk Bones when he goes into his kennel for a bedtime snack. After he eats he has to go potty about 15 minutes after with a brisk walk. 

Happy likes bacon treats after he comes back inside. He likes ice in his water bowl to keep it cool. He is a great dog one on one. Happy loves to be spoiled and does not like to share the attention with other animals including dogs and cats. Happy would be great for someone who loves to explore but also loves to nap. Happy is now fixed, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, up to date on flea/tick/heartworm prevention, and has regularly seen our veterinarian. To meet Happy, please check out our online adoption survey at http://www.secondchancenorman.com/index.php?survey

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Seymour is a 3yr old black and white Pit mix. He has a very playful and loving temperament. He loves squeaky toys and will play fetch. Seymour is housebroken, crate trained, and does ok on the leash. He tends to pull some as he is energetic. He also likes to chatter his teeth. He has no food aggression and gets along will other dogs, no cats! He's somewhat vocal and will alert you when someone is at the door or if outside and prompted by other dogs barking, but will stop on command. He knows to sit, lay, and shake paws He will require a 6 ft fence. Seymour is a sweetheart and loves to please! He is fully vetted, neutered, and microchipped. He will do well in an energetic home. He does great with older kids and all people. Seymour is Lyme+ and currently on meds.

Estimated DOB: 1/14/2018

Adoption fee: $200 (6% KY sales tax included)

We would love to hear from you! To inquire about this dog, please contact us via this site, visit our website sc4paws.org to see a full bio, or visit sc4paws.rescuegroups.org/forms/ to fill out our adoption application.

Important: Our dogs reside in foster homes. Please fill out our adoption application if you would like to meet one of these special dogs!

SCHS Veterinary Care and Services for Dogs (5 months of age and older): Prior to being placed for adoption, all dogs, at a minimum, receive a veterinary exam, are neutered/spayed, tested for heartworms and Lyme disease, and treated for internal parasites, flea/tick preventative , current on booster(s), bordetella and rabies vaccinations.

SCHS Veterinary Care and Services for Puppies (under 5 months of age): Prior to being placed for adoption, all dogs , at a minimum, receive a veterinary exam, are neutered/spayed , and treated for internal parasites, flea/tick preventative , current on booster(s), and rabies vaccinations. Puppies under 4 months of age will be placed into our foster to adopt program until the above services are met.

PLEASE HELP SPONSOR THIS DOG'S FOOD AND VET COSTS BY MAKING A DONATION!

SCHS is a 501(c)-3 nonprofit organization that is volunteer-run.

animal.description:
DO NOT CONTACT THE RESCUE ABOUT THIS DOG. YOU MUST CONTACT THE CURRENT OWNER, CONTACT INFORMATION IS IN THE BIO. If you contact the rescue, you will not get a response as we do not have information on this animal.

Please note that we are unable to receive correspondence through Petfinder’s system. Any messages sent through Petfinder or any buttons on this listing will unfortunately not reach us. 

ARCBCR courtesy lists dogs for individual owners, other rescues, and shelters wishing to place their Border Collies or Border Collie-mixes themselves.
 
These dogs are NOT in the ARCBCR program.

ARCBCR does not warranty any of the information provided about the following dogs. Should any issues arise, ARCBCR will not be held responsible. Fees requested and policies may differ from ARCBCR.

Meet Leo a two year old male (neutered), handsome Border Collie! Leo is an amazing dog, and has so much potential in the right home. He originally was placed as a service dog prospect, and has service dog training. He knows basic commands, is house trained, rides well in the car, is crate trained, does good for grooming, nails etc. He does not have any sound phobias that I have seen. He loves people, especially children! But, he does not do well with other intact male dogs. He wants to correct them for bad behaviors (like if they jump up on you), and that can lead to a fight. He does amazing with my mother's neutered male BC, and my female BC; as well as my three rescues. He does great with small dogs, he is very gentle and mindful around my senior chihuahua. In his last home, he was raised around a small maltese mix. He would do best in a home without cats, as I think he would most likely chase them.  

Leo is located in Seagrove NC, if you would like more information about Leo please email hannahaileen67@gmail.com

animal.description:
Buster ACCT-A-79737
Intake Type: 
(1/21/21) Returned (Aggression towards smaller animals)
(12/28/20) Adopted
(12/17/20) Return ( Buster and resident cat do not get along. Moving)
(11/27/20) Adopted
(11/22/20) Stray
Sex: Male
Age: 3yr
Altered: Yes

Medical Observation: 
(11/22) Normal; tartar

Behavior Observation: 
1/29 (Per Staff) -- Buster should probably be walked with a toy to keep his mouth occupied.
I took Buster out for a walk and he was very easy to leash and bring out of the kennel. Once outside it was very different. He immediately latched onto the leash and started tugging, he refused to let go and would walk while tugging thinking it was a game. He calmed down after many minutes and walked with me past the the large dog runs into the larger parking lot. the whole time he was walking with his tail between his legs. He then proceeded to tug on the leash again and I led him up the stairs into the side entrance. He went into his kennel without a problem. I ended the interaction with a few treats.
1/21 (Per Previous Owner) -- energetic, trained, loyal but aggression towards other animals. sweet to humans, house trained and knows commands. He knowns commands like sit, stay, paw, lay down, up, down. they were working on roll over. Needs a single pet home with a yard
12/27/20 (Volunteer Eval)-- Kennel Presentation--Nervous--On bed on approach but gets up and comes to front of kennel when handler calls for him. Tense body but accepts treats and is leashed without issue. Steps into kennel without issue on return. Is stiff when removing leash but allows leash to be removed.
Leash Skills--Pulls Moderately On Leash
Handleability--Tense/Allows all handling--In run, allows handling all over with tense body. When handler is sitting down, will climb upper body into lap and pushes head against hand for pets but remains tense throughout interaction.
12/17/20 (Per Owner) -- Big cuddle bug, hyper, and super excited to meet people. Does not get along with around animals(gets mouthy and nips them). Learns quickly. Sit, lay down, stay, shake, leave it, come
11/24/20 (Per Staff) -- Took Buster to the meet and greet room with two potential fosters. Buster was very good at first, excited and wiggly. After about 10 minutes he started to get very overstimulated, jumpy and biting his leash. I attempted to pick up the leash and he would snap at the leash near my hand. I got a second leash, and as soon as I tried to leash him he jumped up and bit the new leash, pulled it from my hands and bit through it. I went to get a third leash--this time he snapped at the leash but I was able to leash him. He continued jumping up and snapping several times but then walked pretty well back to the kennel. 
When I went to return him to the kennel he went in easily but then bit the leash again. I attempted several times to remove it, tried to bribe him with treats, but every time I reached to pull it off his neck he would whip his head up to snap at the leash/my hand. Every time he jumped or snapped he was clearly just trying to get the leash, but he did end up snapping close to my hand a few times. I was unable to remove the third leash and left it in the kennel with him.
11/23/20 (Per Staff) -- Nervous in kennel. Whale-eyeing at front of kennel, but sniffed my hand gently and allowed leashing. Exited and re-entered kennel easily. Pulls Moderately On Leash--Strong, may benefit from harness. Tense/Allows all handling--Remained nervous in run but allowed petting and would jump into my lap.
11/22/20 (Per Vet Staff) -- Friendly; BAR
11/22/20 (Per Finder) -- Friendly, loves attention, petting, playful and puppy like, has lots of energy, very strong on leash, was good with finder's cat

BITE DETAILS:
(1/21) Buster bit another dog in an altercation on 1/21/21, but did not bite any humans. No bite quarantine is required. 
(12/17/20) The resident cat was running into the bedroom and Buster started to chase. The adopter went to intervene to separate the two of them and Buster got mouthy. She was able to get the cat in the hamper, Buster bit both the hamper and the adopters left wrist in the process. Level 3A. No medical attention required.
animal.name: Buster

animal.description:
Please read entire posting for information on our new procedures. We are currently requiring appointments for all adoptions.  

Please give us a call if you questions about a pet 

or complete an application at 

https://adoptmountainpets.org/pet-services/adoption-process/application-form 

to make arrangements to visit the Animal Resource Center.

Kola

Just look at those ears!  Kola is a sweet, young (just under a year old) energetic  girl who attaches quickly and loves deeply.   She is looking for a someone who is happy to put the work and care needed to raise her right.  She is dog who loves to use her nose and is happiest doing a job.   Kola would love to meet someone who understands her needs and can give her a job or hobby.  
Please give us call or complete an application on our website.  

970 626 2273

Adopters will be considered on the totality of the application and how it matches the particular pet's needs.

Most dogs who come from the shelter will not be house trained.

We do not know or make guarantees that a dog or cat will do well with all children, other animals or is house-trained.

We will need to talk to all of the adults in the home prior to making an appointment to visit with a pet. 

In most cases its necessary to to have family dogs come into meet your potential adoptee. Please be sure your dogs are spayed or neutered and current on vaccines (distemper - parvo and rabies) before bringing them for a meeting.

All dogs must be transported home in a travel crate to transport your new pup home safely.

Renters must provide a copy of a lease indicating pets are allowed or contact information for the landlord.

Second Chance is happy to have been providing stray, surrender, adoption, and our Community Outreach services throughout the COVID situation.   

All services are provided by appointment only.  Please do not visit the shelter without first making calling the shelter. 

For the safety of our community, staff and volunteers all visitors are required to wear masks and follow the posted social distancing processes *see below.  Do not make an appointment if you are not comfortable following these procedures.  Thank you for understanding and your support.  

If you are interested in meeting or adopting one of our pets or have questions about the process please see our website at www.adoptmountainpets.org or call the Shelter between 11:00 am and 5:45 pm Tuesday through Saturday. 970 626 2273

*  We want to provide you excellent customer service today and keep you and our team safe and healthy. Please read what we are asking you to do today to reduce the risk of spreading COVID-19:

• Maintain a distance of at least 6 feet from other people. Six feet is the average length of many dog leashes but handing a leashes to another person is not maintaining a six foot space.
• Follow staff instructions about how to drop off, pick up or meet a pet.
• If you have any symptoms of illness please reschedule.
• Wear a mask when interacting with staff
• Wash your hands or use hand sanitizer (you can find bottles throughout the property prior to interacting with staff, volunteers or pets.
• Once you have read these guidelines, please tell us you understand them and that you will follow them with at SCHS.
Thank you for your support, for adopting, for fostering and volunteering and understanding our need to do our part in stopping COVID – 19.
animal.name: Kola

animal.description:
What a handsome fella! Vail is about 64 pounds, 2 years old and looks like a Great Pyrenees or Samoyed mix. He has been a wonderful dog inside the home, and an extra fluffy cuddle buddy. We rescued Vail from a Kentucky shelter where he was bound for euthanasia. The hustle and bustle of the city life hasnt been helping Vail decompress well. While at first he was excitedly greeting other dogs and people on walks, he has been growing more reactive to dogs. 

Inside, he is an excellent dog who is gentle, very relaxed and loves to just lounge around by his people or on the sofa. We believe he would do really well in a quiet home, preferably with a yard that he can explore, and with no other dogs or cats. A calmer surrounding can definitely help him gain more confidence and work on his leash manners. 

We know that in the right environment, with a savvy adopter, or foster to adopt home, Vail will make great strides! 

If you think you’re the right fit, have a home without other dogs or cats, and can open your heart and home to help Vail,
apply to adopt at rescuecity.nyc/adopt.


We are currently facilitating safe adoptions with COVID-19 protocols and adopt out to NYC and surrounding states only - NY CT PA & NJ. 

(We will consider other nearby states for adoption on a case by case basis. You must be willing to travel Brooklyn, NY to finalize the adoption.)

**If a dog is listed on petfinder as available then we are still accepting applications for that dog. We urge you to apply as soon as possible to be considered to adopt the dog you’re interested **

Thank you for wanting to give one of our adoptables a loving home! Please follow us on Instagram at @rescuecity for more adoptable updates!

animal.description: Looney Tune.. but, that is a silly name I know. My actual name is Luna! I am a little over 2 years old and I appear to be an Australian Cattle Dog mix. I was surrendered here because my family couldn’t provide care for me anymore. I LOVE people and am super affectionate. I’ll jump in your lap and drench you in kisses. I can be unsure of some handling and fearful to loud noises, so kids over 8 years old is recommended. Toys are my favorite and I will even bring them back for you to throw! We could have A LOT of fun together I think. I am not a fan of cats and can be scared of other dogs. I met a larger dog here and I was scared, but after a little while of hanging out together I would sniff him when he wasn’t looking. I think a calmer dog friend would be best for me as I didn’t really want to be bothered. I also am plenty of pup to be your one and only! That’s all for now folks!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.German Shepherd dogs, as well as the other herding breeds that we have in rescue, are highly active, energetic, working breeds. They require considerable vetting, exercise, socialization, training, leadership and mental stimuli in order to be well-adjusted, well-balanced, and well-mannered dogs. Even if you exercise and play with your dog daily in your fenced yard, you MUST still take your dog out on daily walks and outings in order to work on his/her leash skills, manners, and social skills. These breeds make great additions to active families who will pamper them, but who will also work with them, as they are smart dogs who need leadership, structure, plenty of activity and mental stimulation. If you are new to German Shepherds (and other herding breeds), please research the breed to make sure this is the dog for you. We ask that you consider the time and financial commitment that your German Shepherd (or other herding breed) dog will require before applying for one. Please review the section on our website (www.heartlandgsrescue.org) 'Is a HUGS Dog Right for You?' for additional information.Dutchess is an adorable girl, full of personality, who was rescued from a reservation in South Dakota when she was a tiny puppy. She can be a little sassy but always charming with her big puppy eyes. She is almost 4 years old. Dutchess is around 55 lbs with a beautiful, fluffy coat. She loves toys and treats. She likes to playwrestle and chase and will occasionally get the zoomies. Dutchess loves to go out on walks and explore she is a curious dog so will want to sniff everything that comes across her. She walks well and doesn't pull.
Dutchess needs to be an only dog, with no young kids (no exceptions, please). She needs time to warm up to people. But once that happens, she will love you and ultimately take over your lap, watch movies and will gladly sleep next to you all night.
The adoption fee for Dutchess is $225, all of which goes back into offseting our high-cost vetting expenses and rescuing more dogs. We are a 100% volunteer-run rescue group and rely on adoption fees and donations to continue saving lives. Adoption fees include spay/neuter, current on age-appropriate vaccinations, fecal, deworming, flea/tick and heartworm preventative, heartworm tested if old enough (and treated if positive), and microchipped. Please visit http://heartlandgsrescue.rescuegroups.org/info/adoption for more information about our adoption process and requirements, and to apply. Like any of our dogs, Dutchess would make a great addition to an active home that will provide the love, structure, good leadership, activity and mental stimulation that her breed needs. Because of that, Dutchess's ideal owners will have prior GSD, or other herding breed experience. Even if you exercise and play with your dog daily in your fenced yard, please remember that you MUST still take your dog out on daily walks and outings, in order to provide sufficient stimulation, ward off boredom, and work on leash skills, and manners.Please review the information in the 'About Us', 'Important Considerations' and 'Adopt' sections on our website menu, as it contains useful information about the breed, adoption fees, the adoption process and our requirements, and how meeting the dogs works. 2/2/21 1:19 PM

animal.description:
Leah is a 5 month old, 40 lbs, female lab mix. Leah is house trained.

Leah came to our southern rescue partner around Thanksgiving.  She was surrendered by a family who could  not afford to get her the medical care she desperately needed, since she had a horrible case of demodex mange.  With a lot of medical care and TLC, Leah is now ready to find a forever home.  This girl is so friendly and loves everyone she meets.  She has a lot of energy and would make a wonderful exercising companion.  She is very smart and has already learned some commands, she will focus and wants to learn.  She gets along well with other dogs, cats and even does ok with the chickens in her foster home.    


Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

FOR PUPPIES: PLEASE READ!!
Homes considering Puppies must be prepared for:
Flexible Schedules for Potty Training. Puppies can only hold urine for one hour per month of age. Crate Training for the next 10 months to keep them safe from chewing on everything in your home. Supervision with Children and Obedience training. 
Socialization; both with new people, children and other dogs outside of the home.
Homes that want a well behaved dog, must be prepared to put the time, effort and costs associated to train a puppy. Well behaved dogs are not born, they are trained!  Please do not apply for a puppy if you cannot or do not have the time for a puppy.

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

animal.description:
Hello HAZELNUT. This extra cute girl is hoping to charm her way into your heart and home. Last month, Hazelnut came to us from a Kentucky shelter. She’s about 7 months old and 35 pounds...To think she had been let down by humans in the past and still has so much love to give to anyone receptive to it. Hazelnut is SO SNUGGLY. Her foster mom says she is very affectionate and relaxed around people. She is a bit frightened of other dogs on walks but really wants to play and loves exploring outside. Hazelnut has lots of energy and is still working on her puppy mouthiness so would prefer a home with older children, and an active family who will take her on long walks and hikes. She enjoys spending time in her crate and chewing on her toys. Belly rubs are the key to this girl’s heart and she’ll take any and all the love she can get from people. She would love a home with a big yard to play in and a family that will continue working on her socialization and training.
She would surely make an excellent jogging buddy too, with some leash work. Want to make Hazelnut a part of your home? 

Apply to adopt at rescuecity.nyc/adopt! here. 


We are currently facilitating safe adoptions with COVID-19 protocols and adopt out to NYC and surrounding states only - NY CT PA & NJ. 

(We will consider other nearby states for adoption on a case by case basis. You must be willing to travel Brooklyn, NY to finalize the adoption.)

**If a dog is listed on petfinder as available then we are still accepting applications for that dog. We urge you to apply as soon as possible to be considered to adopt the dog you’re interested **

Thank you for wanting to give one of our adoptables a loving home! Please follow us on Instagram at @rescuecity for more adoptable updates!

animal.description:
Milagro / Female / 3 Years / 40 lbs / Street Mix / Toronto

Meet Milagro! Milagro was rescued off the streets of Mexico when it was clear she had suffered a traumatic injury. Her front leg had an exposed fracture and she was suffering from necrosis of the surrounding tissue. The vets only option at that point was to amputate her leg. After undergoing extensive rehabilitation, Milagro has fully adapted to her new life. Once she was cleared to fly, she made the long trip to Canada in search of her forever home!

Once you are in her circle of trust, Milagro is a total love bug. She loves to be close to her people and will snuggle whenever she gets an opportunity. She is described as playful, excitable, loving, active, affectionate, loyal and curious. The perfect family for Milagro would be an active one who is looking for a perfect adventure companion!

When meeting new people for the first time Milagro will bark and be visibly anxious if someone tries to approach before she is ready. If strangers stand at a distance, avoid eye contact and allow her to approach in her own time, she will do so gently. In order for her become more comfortable with strangers, her trusted humans must always advocate for her safety and space. It takes multiple meetings to earn her trust so adopters should have realistic expectations when meeting her. She has not been tested with children but we predict she would do well with respectful children that are 10+. Adults will need to supervise in the beginning to ensure the children are cognizant of her body language and when she needs space.

Milagro’s fosters have been working diligently to create a successful crate schedule. She is high energy and needs to be encouraged to have calm or down time. She may take a few minutes to settle and it is best her humans are in view and allow her to settle before leaving her alone. She may chew on things when left without supervision so it is best she is left in a puppy proofed space.

Milagro goes for three walks a day of varying duration. After a walk she still needs sufficient time to run around and play in the backyard. She requires a potty break at least every four hours to be successful. On leash she does well but will pull if she wants to do something. She does not like to to be approached by strange people or dogs while on leash. Given she receives adequate opportunities to use the washroom, she is fully potty trained.

Milagro is very smart and eager to learn. She has already mastered sit, lie down, touch, come and relax. She is in the process of learning crate, place and leave it. Milagro will need additional obedience training and training in regards to her resource guarding. She tends to guard her toys the first few days in the home so she will require a structured environment.

Milagro’s ideal home would be a detached house, with a fully fenced back yard. She needs a secured space to get out her zoomies and run around outside. She is best suited for homes outside of the city, where she can work on her confidence building and focus while outside. Adopters should have some dog experience and have a solid understanding of her training and exercise needs. Milagro is nervous of dogs outside but did fine with them when she was living in the shelter. She would likely do well with another calm dog, granted proper introductions are made. Milagro has not been tested with cats.

animal.description:
Meet Chester! Chester is 4-5 years old, 50lb retriever mix. Chester has a very sad story - his owner died and a relative left Chester in the garage, only coming to feed and water him every few days for 2 years! Due to this, Chester had some anxiety when he first arrived in foster care and he always wants to be at his foster's feet! With a regular routine and structure, Chester is blossoming into a lovely dog. He is living with 5 other dogs of various sizes and gets along great with them. He has not yet learned how to play with other dogs but he loves toys and chew toys and playing fetch! He would also be happy as an only dog. Chester would prefer a quiet home with a fenced yard. He is a wanderer so a secure fence is a must. Chester loves attention and is eager for petting, he is housebroken and crate trained and ready to find his forever family! 

The adoption fee for this dog is $350 which includes routine vetting and spay/neuter. 

For more information, please contact khasse@petconnectrescue.org
**If you're viewing this on Petfinder, please visit www.petconnectrescue.org to complete our non-binding application.**

animal.description:
Bruno. Rottweiler. Male. 80 lbs. 1.5 years old.

Bruno was a tiny kid who was given to someone as a gift. Unfortunately that person became ill and couldn’t care for Bruno. So Bruno grew up alone in a garage. Bruno was undersocialized. He only knew walls of his confinement as safe. The family was set to euthanize Bruno and that’s when we intervened.
Bruno went straight into board and train with our trainers at See Spot Run and has come SO FAR. He’s a dog who loves to dog! Leash training is on point. Fetch is fun and even more fun to not bring back the ball. Bruno has a new list for life and loves to learn. He’s looking for an adult only household that understands overcoming a past, loving the present, while ready to have nothing but success in the future. Bruno would love a active household motivated in learning the world together.

animal.description:
Chester is looking for a hero! This cheerful guy seems to have a bright, curious mind and a playful spirit. He is active and eager to join you in all sorts of fun! Unfortunately, he seems to have been dealt a rough hand in life and arrived at the kennel heartworm positive, and with some symptoms that indicate it could be somewhat advanced. Friends of CITY DOGS Cleveland will cover the cost of treatment, but Chester needs a home where he can relax and recover! He'll be treated with a slower, more gradual method than usual and so may need to be on restricted activity for some months. This is a great opportunity for watching some Netflix together on the couch, and exploring all sorts of basic training, food puzzles, and more! While Chester is a fairly lively boy, we think once he settles into his new home he'll be quite content to spend lots of time snuggling. Chester is around 5 years old and weighs 64 lbs.

Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to set up a meet and greet and find out more!
Due to COVID-19, CITY DOGS is currently doing adoptions by APPOINTMENT ONLY. Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to request a meet and greet! 

Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

Hours:
10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

animal.description:
Saul is a senior chihuahua or chihuahua mix. He’s estimated to be 10 years old and weighs 5.8 pounds. According to his foster, “Saul wants nothing more than to be near you at all times. Nothing makes him happier. But he also knows how to occupy himself on his designated comfy spot if you’re busy. He will come running when he sees you sit down though because that’s his most favorite thing! He will even let you carry him around and since he is so tiny, one hand will do so you can still get things done around the house. He LOVES to hide under blankets and chase small toys across the floor...especially ones that squeak.” Saul does have some quirks that would make him do best in a home without children, but he gets along fine with other dogs and cats. To adopt a tiny new best friend, apply at ITVrescue.org.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

Orion is a lovely Doberman about 3 years old. Orion is a happy energetic boy.He would love a home that will take him on adventures, continue his basic obedience training and socialization. He is eager to please and will need a strongwomen leader.

Orion came to us from McFarland Animal control shelter with Mayan.

We hold an event every weekend at our facility on SATURDAY 11-5pm. Please visit our social media platforms for the specifics for each weekend as it changes from week to week. Please find our application at lovejoyfoundation.org when you come to an event please bring that filled out in hand with you. You can find our application at Lovejoyfoundation.orgYou MUST submit an APPLICATION via email in hopes to get an appointment, our application is found on our website lovejoyfoundation.org. We are a Southern California based rescue and do nothing adopt further than an hour from our headquarters in Inglewood, Ca. we do not adopt out more than a 30 minute radius. We appreciate you being understanding and Patient as we attempt to go back to a new normal.

Raz is a chihuahua mix, possibly part Jack Russell Terrier. He has short little legs and a stocky build. He's still quite small, however, at about 10 lbs.

Raz is still learning how to be a pet dog, so he is not yet available. He is a quiet dog but he harasses cats and challenges many male dogs. We recommend he is either an only dog or paired with a female. 

He is not suitable for a house with kids at all — that includes visiting grandkids. 

?He is a loving dog who wants to be with his people. He loves to snuggle and get belly rubs. He is not fond of going outside, even in warmer winter weather so he needs to learn how fun a yard can be.

Raz's forever person will need to be an EXPERIENCED dog owner who can put him in his place and continue his training. No exceptions.?

Below is what her owner writes:

Izzie is a vaccinated, spayed, 5 year old female German Shepherd.
She is about 75lbs
