animal.description:
Please READ entire bio before inquiring on this sweet animal. Due to our large volume of mails we receive daily any email sent without proper information requested will NOT be returned.

Meet El Luchador. He is approximately 12 years old and weighs 13 lb.  He is a great old man with a bit of a hearing issue and some cloudiness in his eyes but he gets around great.  He loves to go for car rides, go for walks and eat. He DOES NOT want to be picked up or anyone in his face or he will turn into El Luchador!!  Other then that he will follow you everywhere and loves to sleep with his foster mom.  NO CHILDREN!  He is looking for his forever home. Could it be with you?

If you are interested in meeting this sweetheart, please provide the following required information:

Your vet’s name and number, your current pet(s) names and if you plan on doing obedience training. When we call your vet and if your pet(s) are not up to date on vaccines, and spayed/neutered we will not be able to adopt to you. Once approved, we will set up a meet and greet with the animal to ensure a good fit. We do not adopt on the spot, and our animals are not on a first come, first serve basis. Please do not inquire on an adoptable animal if you are leaving on a vacation or are not wanting an animal for months and want us to hold the animal for you. We ONLY show dogs at our events that have been properly approved by administration and have APPOINTMENTS! NO EXCEPTIONS!

Adoption fee $200.00

If you have provided all the necessary information and have set up a meet and greet, please join us for our adoption event on SATURDAY, February 6th from 12-2pm at The Tractor Supply Company in Washington Township.

We only accept cash or check payments for our adoptions. Thank you. Due to the current situation we are in with COVID-19, please wear a mask.

Their address is:

Tractor Supply Co.
66143 Van Dyke Ave.
Washington Township, MI 48095

Fido and Fluffy's Rescue, Inc. is a 501(c)3 rescue dedicated to re-homing abandoned animals from throughout the Mid West and Puerto Rico. Therefore, we can’t guarantee the dog’s breed or predict the full grown size or weight. We do our best to answer questions in a timely manner; however, some answers are unknown because we don’t know. Although we usually deal with dogs and concentrate on rescuing chihuahuas, we are also able to take in cats, rabbits, reptiles, and other small animals from time to time.

All of our animals are seen by a veterinarian where they receive a wellness exam, age appropriate vaccines, are heartworm tested (treated if necessary) have a fecal check (treated if necessary), and are spayed/neutered before going to their fur-ever homes. Every animal is kept on monthly heartworm and flea/tic prevention and is professionally groomed!

Most of our dogs have come from the streets, previous neglect and abusive situations, or we have no background information at all. The breed(s) listed for the adoptable animal is a guess. We can not guarantee the breed of the dog listed especially if it is a puppy it could grow up to be a variety of breeds or grow up to be a weight way over or under our guess. If you are looking for a particular breed it is best to adopt an adult animal so we can better tell what breed(s) it is.

Please be aware that we are primarily a small dog rescue and our dogs may not be potty trained. If you are looking for a small perfectly potty trained dog we can not guarantee it. Sometimes there is a lot of work needed to put into the rescue companion but it is so worth it!

Fido and Fluffy is a 100% volunteer foster based rescue. We don’t have a facility or any paid employees. All our adoptable dogs are in foster homes. We adopt dogs by appointment only at the Washington Twp., Tractor Supply store.

Thank you for your support and understanding.

Respectfully,
Fido & Fluffy's Rescue, Inc

animal.description:
Meet JingleBells & Gingerbread! This pair will remain small to medium since they're about 20 weeks and under 20 pounds. They will need a fenced yard to enjoy and are being adopted as a pair. We have no idea what mixes they are.

The last couple of weeks have been dedicated to saving GB's ears. That's right... these grid contraptions were intended to help us NOT have to crop his ears. We should know soon if they were successful but the hopes of all are VERY high.

Here's the deal: JB&GB were once living as a litter of eight newborns. They contracted Parvo, mange, and everyone else died. Only these two survived. When they came to us, post mange and post Parvo, they had severe ear infections. Those caused them to violently scratch their ears to the point of causing hematomas. We surgically repaired them both but GB's ears wouldn't heal. Several trips back to the doctor and several surgeries later, grids were sewn onto his ears to keep them protected yet allow airflow to help them heal. He was a CHAMP through the entire ordeal. GB has now lived 5-6 weeks with a cone on. Yet, his gentle and loving spirit remains! JB, in addition to having her ears drained, also had her own emergency when her spay site opened and her insides began seeping out! Another emergency trip to the vet to correct that, and she was awarded her own cone-time for several weeks.

To say these dogs have been through the wringer is an understatement. They've survived more than any should have to yet they're sweet and loving and playful as can be. They also ADORE one another. They live for outside time, love to explore, wrestle - should enjoy that more soon when there's no signs of a cone impeding them - and really like being a part of a family. They're perfect with the two little girls helping them heal and play nicely with the resident doggies, too.

While they're not QUITE ready to transition to their forever home - we want to be sure his ears are fully healed first - they ARE ready to interview potential families!

Applications for JingleBells & GingerBread @ maxxandme.org

JB & GB are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Their adoption donation is only $500! As with all puppies adopted through Maxx & Me, his adopter will need to commit to continue working with a positive reinforcement trainer of their choice to help him continue to become a well mannered and confident boy.

To meet any of our dogs please fill out an application on www.maxxandme.org.

Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
Hellos!
I am Zeus, and everyone says that my charming smile fits my legendary name.
The first 18 months of my life have been a bit hard because I was tied outside a lot.  During that time, other dogs attacked me. As you can imagine, that was really hard on me, and I am anxious about new situations.  Trusting others will take time, and GPRA volunteers are already helping me.  When I first met them, they gave me chicken treats and showed me lots of affection. WOW, that is really great stuff, and I definitely want more of that kind of life!

Basically, I am a really good boy that needs time to learn how to be an inside dog, patience to teach me dog manners, and lots of love and hugs to build my trust.  In return, I will be your faithful companion and loyal guardian.

Looking for brighter days and a family that will love me forever.

– Zeus
Please email info@greatpyratlanta.com

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Name: Echo
Age: DOB 02/07/2011
Gender: Female
Breed: Rottie
Weight: 62
Dog friendly: Yes
Cat friendly: Dog Savvy can be ok!
Kid friendly: No
House Trained: yes
Crate Trained: yes
Energy level: Moderate
History: Breeder Release
Adoption Fee: $300.00

From the Foster:

Echo is a one of a kind senior lady with a lot of personality, and I've gotten to know very well over the last year and half while we saw her through some medical issues (please see below).

First off, she needs to go to a home with NO KIDS. She does not appreciate their loud noises and sudden movements, and she will bark and lunge towards them if they are doing these things in her general vicinity. I really feel she would do best in a quieter household overall. Our house is very quiet/calm, and we rarely have people over.

She does fine in a crate but has also done fine uncrated and left in a room to free roam. She also has gone to work with me many times, and just sleeps all day under my desk. She is not crated at night, and sleeps on one of the many dog beds or occasionally on the couch or our bed.

She does not signal to go outside, but does great on a schedule, and she has not had any accidents in months. We have a fenced yard so she is mostly used to going off leash, but she has also gone while on leash but it will take her significantly more time to go. She is also a poop eater any chance she gets. On the plus side, while everyone else in MN complains about a poopy yard after the snow melts, yours will be spotless due to you having to pick up poop right away.

She is a mature lady and doesn't come with any of those tiresome puppy behaviors like mouthing, jumping, destroying things that aren't hers, etc.

She lives with two adult human, two other large dogs (65-100#), and a cat. The dogs all get along well, but don't interact much with each other and like to do their own things. They are all more people oriented anyways! She does have some resource guarding with the other dogs when it comes to high value treats and toys. She has not guarded anything from me, but has with my boyfriend. If she can be left alone to enjoy her special treat/toy, that is ideal. She will also accept a trade for something else! She has been to the dog park and mostly just keeps to herself but is interested in what the others are doing. I do not think she knows how to play with another dog, and would probably do best in a household with low-key dogs. She would also be fine with no other dogs in the family. She had a difficult time with the cat for the first few weeks she was here. She was very fixated on him. We did total separation for awhile, then eventually eased off, and by that time, the novelty had worn off. Now she hardly glances his way and I've found them sleeping on the couch together a few times. She should either go to a cat-free home, or to one where it is possible to separate for as long as necessary, and ease into things. My cat is middle aged and pretty mellow, so I don't know how she would do with a more active cat. She does have prey drive with critters in the yard and on walks (squirrels, rabbits, etc).

She is unsure of new people at first, especially when meeting on her territory - she will bark at new visitors who come into the house, or when the human neighbors are out in the yard (doesn't care about their dogs). She does not like to be towered over and is unsure about deep, gruff voices. Other than when strangers encroach on her territory, she is not a vocal dog.

Once you are "her people," she is the sweetest, goofiest dog. She does a little dance with her nubby tail wiggling when we come home. She loves to be pet and have her ears rubbed, and her head becomes dead weight in your hands. Aside from that, she's not a super cuddly dog who will want to curl up next to you on the couch, but she shows affection in her own way. She loooves tennis balls and to chase after them in the yard, or throw them around for herself to chase after. The squeaky ones are even better. She loves stuffed Kongs and all treats/bones/toys. She enjoys walks and does well on a leash and walking past other dogs, but does not have a ton of stamina to go long distances, especially in warm weather. (She loves a good dog stroller ride if you have one!) If you try to lift her up for any reason, she becomes a sack of potatoes and sinks into the floor. She loves car rides and when she knows you are getting ready to leave, will race to the door and just sit and wait. She is the best errand buddy and immediately passes out in the backseat. She often lays with her front legs crossed. She sleeps hard and snores. She farts often and loudly and doesn't care if it's at work during a meeting.

Echo is a super special dog who needs a patient, calm, loving family committed to always setting her up to succeed and providing her the absolute best care through her twilight years. After 8 years of a mediocre breeder dog life, it's what she deserves.

From our Vets: Echo has a history of recurrent UTIs that needs to be medically managed. Adopters should consider that her veterinary care needs to be more regular. She needs to remain on the Pala-Tech cranberry supplements lifelong, have her blood work checked every 6-12 months, and have a urinalysis and urine culture and susceptibility test run every 3-4 months.

If you think your home would a good match for Echo, apply today to meet her!

animal.description:
*Not suited for an apartment* 
*Structural fence required, door darter*
*No kids*

Poptart came to The Animal Care Society from an overcrowded rural shelter. He was just skin and bones when we got him. We are still working on putting weight on him but he has made a lot of progress so far. We aren't sure what all Poptart went through before coming here, but it has left him with some emotional scars. He is very scared of everything and everyone around him. You can tell that he wants so badly to come up to you for affection, but he is just too nervous. We have learned that when he's alone he can be somewhat destructive. This could change once he's in a home but we recommend that he goes into a crate when no one is around to supervise him. Poptart needs to go to a quiet home with a fenced-in yard. Because of his nervousness, he cannot go to a home with children. He seems to enjoy the company of other dogs, but he will steal food or treats from them which could end up causing an unwanted altercation, so he would need to be fed separately from other animals. Poptart needs someone to show him that whatever has happened to him in the past, is behind him. If you are interested in adopting Poptart, please put in an application on our website www.animalcaresociety.org. animal.description:
Beautiful Salem has cast a spell on us! This husky mix is about 49 pounds and 2 years old. Nine weeks ago today (1/22/21), Salem birthed eight BEAUTIFUL babies. Her #broodofbroomriders are nearly ready for their forever homes but Salem, definitely is! She has been a spectacular mother! She nursed, cleaned, doted on, disciplined, played with and taught her babies the last nine weeks and now... they're driving her bananas! Like all new mommas, Salem is craving adult time. So yesterday, she went to day care and LOVED it! Salem will be spayed next week and then on the hunt for her forever family! She will require a large fenced yard to enjoy and would like another playful friend but it isn't necessary. Salem isn't a fan of being left alone for long periods - she's a sensitive Husky mix gal - so someone home mostly is key. Salem is VERY friendly, VERY playful. Because she is so very Husky, a home with no cats, no small dogs, and no prey animals of any kind will be necessary. Salem runs like the wind and couldn't be any faster if she was riding a broom; so, a home with a securely fenced yard will be needed. Salem is enchanting. We know she will steal your heart as quickly as she stole ours. She is friendly with other respectfully playful pups and was drawn to the pre-teen she met today. An active family who can exercise Salem, play with her, and then let her crash with you is exactly what this girl needs.

It's time to show Salem the dedication and commitment she has shown her brood. We need someone committed to loving this girl fully and forever! Applications for Sweet Salem @ maxxandme.org

Salem will be spayed soon, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Adoption donation is $250.
If you would like to meet any of our dogs, please fill out a foster or adoption application on www.maxxandme.org
Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
Cowboy is a sweetheart. This handsome, playful lab mix is about 45 lbs and 4 years old. He would do best with some outdoor space to play in and regular exercise. but when playtime is over he is a gentle angel. He is fine with other dogs. Cowboy likes his crate and is doing great with housebreaking. Cowboy is a love and will make a great companion or family dog.

Please email us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com to find out if Cowboy is the right one for you! (Local adoptions preferred - Philadelphia and tri-state area [South Jersey and northern Delaware] only.)

PLEASE READ BEFORE CONTACTING US!
We are NOT a shelter: All of our dogs live in private homes with foster families. Come and meet the Almost Home dogs and their fosters at our Meet & Greet events, where you can learn more about our wonderful dogs from the people who live with them, find out which dogs are on their way and when they'll arrive, and fill out an application to adopt or foster.

We cannot adopt to homes where electric-shock fencing systems or training collars are used. For more information on the dangers of electric-shock collars, please visit banshockcollars.ca/studies.php and http://www.hollysden.com/say_no_to_shock.htm (scroll down and click on the "Invisible Fencing Systems" link).

We do not have an online adoption application; to request an application, e-mail us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com. To speed e-mail processing time, be sure to note the name of the dog you are inquiring about in the Subject line. For Meet & Greet times and locations, visit our home page, where you also will find information on our adoption process and fees.

FOSTER FAMILIES ARE LIFESAVERS!! Can you open your heart and home for a few weeks to homeless shelter dog? Remember, by fostering a dog, you save TWO lives - that of your foster dog, and that of the dog who takes his place in the shelter! Come to a Meet & Greet and find out if fostering is for you - there's no reward quite like the feeling that you've saved a life ... or two!

animal.description: Myla is a sensitive girl who has been very fearful in the shelter. But we have learned the way to her heart- squeaky toys!! She loves them all! Once she's comfortable, she is fun to play with and enjoys walks. She is very nervous around new people and will take an extended amount of time to warm up. She will need a patient, experienced owner who is willing to use positive reinforcement training and to give her all the time she needs to warm up. Her new home should have a fenced yard and should be without kids under 14. She can be posessive of toys and food around other animals and will need to be the only pet in the home. Myla may never be a good dog to take to social functions, but would prefer someone who can spend a lot of time with her one on one.

Lila Belle is a 6-year-old pit/hound mix. She was brought to a rural Alabama shelter as a stray & never reclaimed. Lila Belle was very emaciated when she arrived, but has been steadily gaining weight! 

Lila Belle is a super sweet girl! She's very lovable & affectionate. She likes other dogs, but is a little awkward with other dogs. We don't think she ever learned how to play with other dogs. She's been doing well in her play group & is picking up skills quickly! Lila Belle is medium energy. She's equally happy exploring the outdoors as curled up cuddling with you! She's going to make a wonderful companion!




COMPLETED APPLICATIONS TAKE PRECEDENCE OVER INQUIRIES! IF you are interested in adopting, the FIRST step is to complete an application! Please email for an Application or copy and paste the following URL: 

https://fs26.formsite.com/nogreaterlove/form2/index.html 

Upon receipt of your application, the rescuer and foster in AL will contact you so you can ask any specific questions you may have! If there is more than one decision maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement! 

 Adoption Donation: Unless otherwise stated in the pet's bio, our standard adoption fee is $250 which covers age appropriate vaccines (DHPP vax) and (Rabies vax if 12 weeks and older), utd on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, worming, heartworm test @ age 6 months or older, microchip, fostering costs and health certificate.

Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21

animal.description:
Arabella is a 1.5 year female that weighs 50 lbs. Our vet believes she is a boxer mix. Arabella has one of the showiest brindle coats we have seen! And it’s very soft, perfect for petting. Arabella was found as a stray and it did take some work to catch her. For that reason, a calmer home will probably be a better fit. Kennel staff says she does have a playful side and enjoys romping in the yard. She’s such a gentle soul and once she realizes she’s home, she’s going to fall hard for you. A dog that truly knows she’s been rescued. Arabella can do meet and greets with other dogs, but she is too interested in cats. To adopt this brindle beauty, apply at ITVrescue.org.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

Katie is a young adult, spayed female who is full of energy. Katie loves to be given attention and does eventually calm down with petting. She does need a handler who can help teach her manners. She tends to pull very hard on the leash and she likes to jump up on people. Katie will need to go to a home with a fenced in yard to make room for her zoomies and to accommodate her active lifestyle. With a little work, this sweet girl will make a great addition to a family. 

**COVID PROCEDURE***  Please fill out an adoption application at www.cedar-rapids.org/animal. After the application is submitted, a staff member will contact you to schedule an appointment to meet the pet!

* The spay/ neuter surgery is included in the adoption fee of $125.

* We always prefer that our animals go to indoor homes.

*OWNING a pet is a life time commitment!  Please be ready to make that commitment before you adopt a pet!

*BREED DISCLOSURE: Due to the fact that most of our adoptable pets are strays, we can not guarantee their breed. We list the pets breed as the one that best matches the physical appearance, temperament, and personality of the animal-in some cases it's purely a guess. The pet may also be listed as a mix when it’s actually a purebred.

Online Adoption Application 
Hi I'm Cody! My original family surrendered me because they could no longer afford the bills that came with owning a pup. I'm the biggest snuggle bug. I'm a mountain of love and energy and make a great 40lb lap dog. Ear scratches, belly rubs and food are my jam. At only a year, I'm in my awkward phase of having a puppy brain in a grown pup body. I need an active family that will take me on walks, hikes, and preferably has a fenced yard. I'm very smart and pick up new things quickly! After only 3 days, I learned sit and wait at my foster home. I'm working on leash manners, stay, and leave it. I'm looking for a furever family that will love me for always!
I am crate trained and house trained. I do great with people. I'd do best in a home with older kids. I don't know anything about cats as I've never met one before. My foster home has one other dog that I get along with great (one could say we are besties)! Are you my pawfect match?

animal.description:
Dylan is an 8 year old Staffordshire Terrier looking for his forever home.  He wants to be king of the castle, so no other dogs or cats for him. He dies love his humans and will snuggle up with you as you binge watch your favorite shows.  If you would like to learn more about Dylan, please complete an application and then reach out to Roxy@bigfluffydogs.com

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1.

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time.

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Meet Bella! Prior to coming to Homeward Trails, she was surrendered to Fayette County, WV shelter with her three 9-week old puppies. She is a happy, medium size, super wiggly and friendly girl. She plays well with other dogs and would be a great companion to someone or another pet. If you think you might be a fit for being her new forever family, please submit an application to meet her at our adoption center soon!

Adoption Coordinator: Adoption Center
Location: Adoption Center
The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee includes spay/neuter and microchip.

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
A LAID-BACK GENTLEMAN:  13 years old / 21 lbs. and needs to lose some weight

Hi, my name is Murphy!  Somehow, I ended up at animal control, so Mostly Mutts has stepped in to be sure I spend my golden years receiving the love and care that I deserve.  I have one eye (and sight in it is limited due to age) and some hearing loss which is typical at my age as well. 

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  I met the other dogs in my foster home and do fine with them, though we don’t interact or play, so if you have a nice doggie who isn’t looking for a playmate, let’s meet / Cats unknown, but I likely would not be interested in them / I also haven’t met kids yet at Mostly Mutts, but older kids may be best in my new home.  I am a senior guy, and younger children may expect me to be playful, and I am not.

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  My foster describes me as a ‘sweet gentleman’ who is happiest just chilling with my people, so if you are looking for a TV or book reading buddy – sign me up!  Long or short life ahead of me – I want to live large in comfort and love.  Since I have sight loss please keep me safe from falling down the stairs and out in the yard etc.  / My energy level is 1-3.

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I don’t know any doggie commands, but I don’t mind – I’m all good / I don’t use a crate in my foster home / I need frequent let outs to avoid potty accidents, and I need to go out right away upon waking from a nap.  My foster uses a belly band with me, though it does not always stay on – losing weight should help with this.  My foster has learned my potty habits (if I get up and immediately start walking around, its potty time), so accidents have decreased.  I’ve also just started a medication to help with incontinence.

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I love the closeness of being with my people and enjoy hanging out or napping near my people on the couch.  You’ll want to keep a pee pad on there, as I sometimes have accidents in my sleep.  I also enjoy treats / I can’t think of any dislikes, but I would not be happy if I didn’t get the love and attention on which I thrive.

• MEDICAL:  I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and neutered.  I am on special kidney food and taking medicine to help with my incontinence.  I also take glucosamine and fish oil to help keep my joints as healthy as possible.  I’ve just had a dental cleaning, so the remaining teeth I have are healthy again!  

I am looking for a special family who will give me the love I deserve in my golden years.  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.
animal.name: Murphy

Sweet Nell has a way of charming people. In October she was taken to Countyview Vet in Kinston to be treated for a neck injury, apparently from a dog attack. They liked her so much that after she was treated,  they committed to keep her until a good rescue situation was found. So she arrived at Red Barn Rescue on January 20th and is winning our hearts already!

Nell is a 22-pound Feist mix, approximately 3 to 5 years old. She likes dogs and plays well with dogs of similar size. She loves her walks and would enjoy an owner who wants a walking partner. She is bright-eyed and alert, enjoys sniffing and investigating as she walks. 

She is a little careful of new people, but within minutes her tail is wagging and she is receptive and loving.  Her past is unknown, but because she is a bit uncertain of some circumstances we think her owners should be adults without small kids which may make her nervous. 

Nell will be spayed, microchipped, vaccinated and up to date on heartworm and flea/tick preventative. She had tested positive for heartworms and has already begun treatment. Our $300 adoption fee helps to cover these expenses.

animal.description:
Bobino is an estimated 12 year old chihuahua, that weighs in at about 7 pounds.

He's an unsure boy, of life around him, but he doesn't take long too warm right up to anyone who gives him kindness and love and move into high cuddling gear.

He found himself in a Canadian shelter, after his owners said they had suddenly developed an allergy to him.  We think it's more based on his medical needs, as Bobino arrived to us with a bad cough, and after seeing our cardiologist, it was determined he has mitral valve insufficiency.  

________________________________________

Clinical History:

Grade 5/6 murmur. Coughing. Started furosemide 5 mg BID and doxycycline yesterday.

Echocardiographic Findings [Keith A. Blass, DVM, MS, DACVIM (Cardiology)]:

There is moderate to severe left atrial dilation (LA 28.1 mm). The mitral valve leaflets are thickened and exhibit systolic prolapse. A moderate to severe jet of eccentric mitral regurgitation is present. There is moderate to severe left ventricular dilation (LVIDd 28.9 mm; LVIDs 15.3 mm). Left ventricular systolic
function (FS 47%) is hyperdynamic. The aorta and aortic valve appear normal, though trace aortic insufficiency is present. Right atrial and right ventricular dimensions are normal. The tricuspid appears normal, though trace tricuspid regurgitation is present. TR velocity (TR 2.78 m/s) does not suggest the
presence of pulmonary hypertension. 

The pulmonary artery and pulmonic valve are normal. No pericardial effusion or cardiac masses are seen.
  
ECG: Sinus arrhythmia

Assessment/Recommendations:
Degenerative mitral valve disease

This examination demonstrates moderate to severe mitral regurgitation resulting from degenerative valve disease. Secondary to his regurgitation, Bobino has moderate to severe dilation of both his left atrium and left ventricle, though his left ventricular systolic function is well-preserved. 

Given the severity of his disease, Bobino is at relatively high risk for the development of left-sided congestive heart failure, and it’s likely that mainstem bronchial compression is contributing to his cough.

Continued use of furosemide appears to be warranted based on this exam, as is therapy with benazepril (1.25 mg BID), and pimobendan (1.25 mg am, 0.625 mg pm), as these medications should help to improve any cardiogenic component of Bobino’s cough, as well as slow the progression of his cardiac disease.
________________________________________

Bobino will need to be on heart medication the rest of his life (estimated to be about $100/month), so this is something you must take into consideration when adopting and we highly suggest you speak with your veterinarian about the medication costs when considering this boy.

With his heart medication, he can go on to live a really terrific, long life.  But we absolutely can not guarantee this, but typically it's a really slow progressing disease that responds well to medication.  Speak with your veterinarian for their opinion on the case.

Bobino is a really fun little dog.  He's not a fan of other dogs, but is in foster with other dogs and being tolerable.  We'd love to see this boy in a quiet home to call his own, as an only pet.

You must love walking, because this boy is a walker and gets REALLY excited when he can get out and adventure in the world.

Bobino also showed signs of separation anxiety the first few days of being in foster when his foster Mom went to work, but slowly settled into a routine and manages fine on his own.  That said, a home where someone is home most often or can take their dog to work is what we'll be seeking for Bobino.

Bobino is just a super quirky guy, that likely has been unsocialized in life,  that now deserves lots of love and compassion and an opportunity to live a really amazing rest of his life.

------------------------------------
FROM HIS FOSTER MOM:

He’s awesome! 

He needs a lot of love. Approach him slowly but he definitely likes to be pet and loved. Just leery at first.

He kept jumping up on the front of the couch wanting to come up and join me...and gives kisses! And he lets me pick him up and cuddle. He also likes to snuggle up in bed. He knows how to get to my heart!! ?

He’s super spry!! No apparent issues with joints or pain. Great walker.

He’s cautious of the dogs but it's manageable.
------------------------------------

FROM THE INTAKE FORM SHELTER/PREVIOUS OWNER:

Was living w/ 2 seniors 
Was getting along w/ everyone in the home – per owner 
Fearful, vocal w/ house guests – per owner 
Unknown w/ kids – per owner 
Unknown w/ dogs, never in contact. Barks when sees them - per owner 
Personality: active, excited, affectionate, playful and fearful – per owner 
Has been seen by the vet this past year for coughing – per owner 
House trained on pee pads – per owner 
Eats kibbles from vet clinic – per owner 
Not crate trained – per owner 
Calm when left alone – per owner 
No bite history – per owner 
Have to respect his “bubble”, if approached too fast he can charge. Other than that he is ok – per owner  
Does not like sudden movements – per owner 
Bad habits: vocal, afraid of thunderstorms, reactive on leash – per owner 
Loves car rides – per owner 
Nervous disposition + does not like being held – per owner 
Used to go to groomer – per owner 

____________________________________________

As of today, though our protocols could change tomorrow, we are still moving forward with adoptions. Our process has changed from some of the previous elements: We are a registered animal welfare organization, so we are deemed an essential service.

All paperwork completed online, video home visits, meet and greets outside respecting social distancing, leashes/collars/supplies wiped down and disinfected (GermiCide 3 wipes), disinfectant on the dog prior to handoff (Aqueos wipes for dogs)

-----------------------

To note: the above description is relevant to this dog in his current setting. Home changes & adopter personalities can bring out different behaviours not previously seen.

We do not specifically kid/cat test our dogs when they arrive at Mattie's Place. That just wouldn't be fair to the dog or child/cat.

We also do not claim, endorse, suggest or hint at, that any of our dogs are hypoallergenic, low shed or no-shed.

Adoption fee includes: spay/neuter, deworming, defleaing, vaccinations, nose to tail health exam, leash|collar, 6 months of preventative based on season/need, DNA test for entertainment purposes, dishes, poop bags, food and any extras she has accumulated in foster care.

animal.description: Meet Indigo! This beautiful Husky mix is about 5 years old, fully vetted, and ready to find a wonderful forever home! Indigo was surrendered to the shelter after being too rough with the kids in the home. Her previous family told us that she does well with other dogs as long as they aren't puppies, she wasn't around cats, and she usually did well with their kids but she can get a little too rough sometimes. Indigo is potty trained, knows basic commands, and walks well on a leash! She does well on car rides and was described as friendly, playful, noisy, outgoing, high energy, cuddly, and protective. Indigo loves to run and go for walks and once she has had her exercise she mellows out quite a bit. She is cuddly, loves milkbones for treats, and doesn't like people messing with her tail. Indigo loves to be around other dogs but she can't be around puppies. She will need frequent grooming and daily exercise in her new home! If you would like to meet Indigo give us a call so we can set up an appointment!

animal.description:
Charlie is the happiest dog around, who is looking to find a forever family! Charlie is housetrained, incredibly sweet, and would love to meet you! He loves to stay near his human companion for cuddles, and enjoys gentle leash walks and playing fetch. He would be a wonderful companion in a home with older children who would love to work with him on his basic commands that he is learning and play ball with him!

Charlie is currently in a foster home, and his foster family says that:

"Charlie is a very happy, sweet dog who wants to please. He would enjoy (but not need) being in a placement with another dog, as he is so social and thrives on interaction. He is remarkably active for an older dog, and he needs an owner(s) who will take him on a long walk every day once he completes heartworm treatment."
 "Charlie is completely housetrained. Bottom line, he is a very happy, friendly dog who wants to please. Medium energy--he gets up in the morning quite energetic and wants to play and jump up on me and constantly interact. He is fairly content being outside by himself, and as he has gotten more used to being here, he is starting to "guard" the yard and bark sometimes at things he sees, which is a good job/challenge for him. He hasn't been an excessive barker at all. When he can't spend time outside, going on a walk or throwing the ball every couple of hours helps to meet his need for physical and mental exercise. 
I think that he would love to be in a house with another dog, and this would help to channel his energy. My guess is that he would be too cluelessly energetic with a cat--he has more friendly enthusiasm than good manners."

The foster also says that "He would enjoy children, but he would knock over smaller children when he is in one of his enthusiastic moods. He is very strong for his size and he needs ongoing work to stop his jumping up on people when he is overly energetic. 
It is important to teach Charlie basic commands such as no, sit, stay, lie down, which will provide structure for him and help him feel safe. It seems that someone has taught him to drop the ball in front of his person after he retrieves it. This is success that he could continue to work on.
He is okay in a crate. I usually leave him in the crate no more than an hour. He sleeps on my bed, but I think he would get used to being in the crate at night. He settles down very quickly to sleep and is a very good sleeper.
He needs something to chew on both inside and outside. He has a ball in the yard and a couple inside since they get misplaced sometimes. A rubber ball is his favorite--don't bother with tennis balls, as he destroys them in minutes! He much prefers a rubber ball over the rubber bone that I got him."

Charlie does have some issues with his esophagus that make him cough occasionally, but using a harness for walks helps tremendously!


Do you think I am the perfect match for you? Click on the link below for the Meet Your Match questionnaire. We will forward your information to the foster parent for follow up. This information will be used to make sure this is a good fit before we schedule a meet and greet.
Let's get started on meeting me! https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSeOSn7D67PzZ98rWlpCkNUL9aaxFLVAk7m1ucMF3fFj7JWzgQ/viewform?usp=sf_link

animal.description: Hey there, I'm Daphne! I was found as a stray following strangers at the park and, after trying to find my family, they brought me here to the shelter. I think I'm the sweetest 52lbs you'll find anywhere. I'm generally calm, easy going, tolerant of almost everything and friendly with people. I'm easily collared and leashed, but my walking habits can be hit and miss (sometimes I'm a little too eager to get to the next destination). I love soft/squishy blankets, bones, treats, car rides and spending time with humans. Though I warm up quickly, I'd like to meet any fur-siblings before going home (just to make sure it's the right fit for everyone). I'm so excited to find my loving forever home.

animal.description:
Please note donations using the SPONSOR ME tab will not go to Fluffy Dog Rescue.

To Locate Our Application go to http://rescue.fluffydog.net/how-to-adopt.html

Our listings are updated throughout the day. If there is an applicant, it will say PENDING ADOPTION next to the dog's name. If not, please submit an Application that can be found on our site, www.fluffydog.net. 

MY AGE: approx. 2 yrs  WEIGHT: approx. 38 lbs.  WHERE I AM FROM: AL (arrival 1/30) 

MY STORY: Buddy was a neighborhood stray. 

Great inside dog, few mistakes. Was great at the vet. Was worried to begin with but loves strangers. Absolutely hates crates, being confined for any reason. Gives kisses, sleeps on the couch. Doesn’t play with the other dogs, would prefer people. Not mean to them, just loves sitting by us. Doesn’t like many treats, but loves his food with warm beef broth mixed in. Would do great with a single guy that dotes on him. Would still leave if he would get out the front door as he was a wanderer for so long, but would come back at dinner. Loves being outside or inside. Did I say- hates crates and confinement ?. I’ll have to give him something for transport to make it in his crate.

Dogs are held for two weeks after arrival date. You are welcome to apply, but applications will be processed closer to the available date.

Dogs needing foster homes are available for adoption This dog does need a foster home. Have you ever considered fostering a dog?  For more information, see the Fluffy dog rescue home page. This dog does shed and is not hypoallergenic.

HOUSEBROKEN?   GOOD WITH DOGS?  Yes  GOOD WITH CATS?unknown

ADOPTION FEE: $450

To adopt the FIRST STEP is to complete an APPLICATION. The application can be found on our site www.fluffydog.net, or by clicking on the purple Fluffy Dog Rescue wording found in the left corner of this page under the dogs name.

Our dogs are located in foster homes throughout the state. We do not have a facility. Adopters must be 24 years old.We can not adopt to families with children under the age of six. We also adopt in WI, IL, and parts of MN. Most of our dogs are strays, so the breed is our best guess.
WI License #270548.
 
Check out Fluffy Dog Wellness on our Home Page. Great Solutions to Enhance Your Pet's Health. www.fluffydog.net

animal.description:
These two pups need help, they are being surrendered and need to find a new home together.  Their current home is being told they can only keep one and they can’t tear them apart and would rather they find a new home together.  The male (Tri Color) is Daredevil, AKA Devil. He is 6 years old and quite possibly the chillest dog on earth. He is neutered and has had his first and second shots. He is, obviously, overweight and is something they have been working on for some time. Aside from that he is very mild tempered and calm, he is the best cuddle buddy on earth. He loves hanging out with you no matter what you are doing.  The Black and White is a female and her name is 
Indianna Joanna Jones, AKA Indie. She is 5 years old and is the complete opposite of Devil. She is not spayed (but will be before they are adopted out) and has only had her first shots (she will be getting her second set once she gets into her foster home). She is the healthiest of the two, thankfully. She is very hyperactive and loves to be all up in your business! No matter what you are doing she will want to do it with you. She would be a good jogging buddy for sure. Although she is always down for cuddles too.  We believe these two pups have been around people who were on meth and abused them.  They are bonded and Devil completely relies on Indie to keep him happy and warm.  These two are looking for a home that will give them love and allow them to be together.  We are looking for a foster home for these two until little Indie can be spayed, then will be taking applications for their adoption.  If you would like to meet them to see if they would be a good fit at your home please fill out an application at

www.lowridersofthewest.org

Whey would make the best companions for anyone wanting a walking partner or just a couple of snuggle bugs.

animal.description:
If you always knew you wanted two pups, here's your opportunity.  This two were made for each other and for their lucky Pawrent!    Leo, 52lbs and tall, dark and handsome and dainty 18lb Reyna have discovered life is better together.  They are both about 11-months-old and medium energy.  They love each other and Reyna is a good influence on shy, skittish Leo.   They love to play together, (watch video) walk together and nap together.  

Reyna is absolutely fearless of everything and has never met a dog or person she doesn't love.  She's ready to get the party started at the drop of a hat but is also crate trained and will settle in for a good nap if nothing is going on.  Leo is a shy kind of guy who gains confidence around his girlfriend.  Currently, they sleep together in a crate and that's the way they like it.   Leo will take a while to warm up to people and will do best in a quiet home with no children because kids can overwhelm him.  If he could choose his perfect home, it would be a home headed by a woman who could give him the time and patience to learn to trust but having his girlfriend with him ensures he will get there quickly.

animal.description: It breaks our hearts that such a good boy is down on his luck these days. Nash was adopted as a puppy but was re-homed a few weeks ago due to a fight with the other dog in his home. (We have no clue who started it, and they had always been buddies, so it's def strange.) He was adopted and doing very well, but sadly, his new mom is very sick right now, and she can't care for him. SOOOO.....here we go again. Nash is a house trained 1 year old, 60 lb Pit mix who may look tough, but he's actually a mushy lover boy. He's is a very affectionate boy who absolutely LOVES all people and always has to be touching someone when cuddling. Hes loves happy to play and has typical puppy energy (although not an excessive amount), but his favorite activity is snoozing outside in the warm sunshine. He's a work in progress on the leash, but he's getting there! We're looking for home with loving parents who understand that Nash has been bounced around and are willing to give him the time and patience he needs as he settles in. We'd prefer he be an only dog in his new home. Nash is neutered, microchipped, and vaccinated, and his adoption fee is $400.

Please contact Cindy Robinson (cindyrobinson@hswctn.org) for more information about this pet.All HSWC animals are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and up-to-date on vaccinations before adoption (if species appropriate).
Application and counseling is required prior to all adoptions.

Individuals interested in adopting a puppy are STRONGLY encouraged to download and read this FREE ebook. Even if you've raised puppies in the past, this is an invaluable resource to help make your new addition successful!

"Hi there, my name is Lefty! I am a long-legged handsome boy with a knack for adventure. I might be big, but I do not realize my own size. I love to explore the outdoors with a human by my side. I enjoy playing fetch and have a pony-like gallop. My floppy ears are quite endearing.
I like toys with squeakers and my favorite snack is a Kong filled with peanut butter. I am not a big cuddler, but I am content being by your side while you watch television, cook dinner, or read a book. Small children tend to make me nervous, so for this reason I would do better in a home with mature children or adults only. Dogs interest me quite a bit and I feel that, with a proper introduction, I could make a furry friend or two! I have so much potential and want a family of my own to give me the love and attention I deserve! "

Lefty is currently attending training with GymDog in Johnson City. He is doing extremely well in meeting his true potential.

If interested in the handsome guy, please email humanesociety@hswctn.org for more information.

animal.description:
Hi friend! I'm Goose! I'm a wild and playful pup, and I LOVE a good game of tug! I've got a purple dot because I have had no training in the past, and I definitely need it to be a good companion. I'd do best with an experienced dog owner with no children at home so that I can safely learn my manners. Lucky for me, my pals at HSSC are including free obedience courses with my adoption! I'm very rude with other dogs, so I'd probably be best suited as an only dog. I REALLY like to play with toys, I'm not picky at all. Some might say I like them a little too much; I can be very snappy taking toys, so I need to learn "drop it" and "leave it" to make playtime safer. As you can probably tell, I have lots of energy and I need room to move, so I'd do best in a single-family home as opposed to an apartment or condo. If you have a backyard, I'd be thrilled! If not, I hope you're a runner! If you understand my needs and you're ready to take me home, please come to see me! Maybe we can have a slumber party!

What's HW+? I'm currently being treated for heartworms. I'll need to keep a calm lifestyle until finished and may require an appointment or two. Please don't be deterred, my lifespan isn't shortened, and I'm not contagious to your other pets.

Take me on a Slumber Party! You can bring me home for a 3 day - 30 day trial period. HSSC will provide food, medications, and necessities. If I'm not the one for you, just bring me back to HSSC and provide feedback on what would be the best home for me.

animal.description:
Lily is a sweet and spunky little chihuahua; she is 9 years old and approx. 6 pounds

She takes time to warm up to new people and will likely bark at them inside or outside of the home but warms up relatively fast (usually within an hour or two) as long as they respect her space and let her come to them.

She is great with cats and the foster parent's larger dog but not tested with small dogs. She isn't afraid to tell them if they are bothering her and likes her space when resting but does so in an appropriate manner.

Lily loves going for walks; she did show some reactivity towards people but that has calmed down for the most part, although she continues to be reactive to dogs when out. We have not tried on leash greetings so we are not sure how she would do. Lily gets nervous of busy streets, loud noises and spooks if something touches her (like her leash) but has good recovery. She also tends to bark at noises she hears in apartment hallways, doorbells and other dogs barking.

It is a joy to come home as Lily is always excited to greet people she knows with silly dances and full body wags. She enjoys playing with soft toys and her humans as well as trying to play with the resident cats even though they aren't open to playing back.

Lily enjoys cuddling with her humans but is also happy to find a soft bed or couch to nap on alone.

We are currently enrolled in a virtual training class for basic obedience and she is catching on quickly. She is learning her sits and downs (although not comfortable doing them unless on something soft like a bed or towel). We are starting to learn loose leash walking and mat work which she loves! She also knows touch and recall indoors.

Lily will eventually need dental work but is otherwise rather healthy. She is fine going up and down stairs and is happy to go on walks to sniff and explore.

Lily would likely do fine in a home with other animals but happy to be the only dog as well.

She can be sensitive about her nails being clipped. We can wipe her paws with a cloth but she does try to pull away. She is okay with getting her sweater and coat on but she still gets nervous while it's being done. No biting or snapping but she's not a fan

She would not be suited to a family with young chidren; that was the reason she came into rescue because she was struggling to live with the toddler

animal.description:
Our adoption area is limited to UT, NV, ID, OR, WA and MT with a home visit. If you are outside of this area please do a search for your local GSP/GWP/Pointer rescue group.

--------

WELCOME SMORE! (you pushy, dominant, noisy, uninhibited boy, you!) ?  Smore spent Two Whole Days at Casa UPP....... during which he learned not to whine in his crate, fling himself against the crate to get to the cats, bark every time he heard something new.......... and He Had A Bath! ?  Omygoodness!  Rescue Lady is  getting too old for these willful 3-year olds!  

On the bright side Smore really wants to be a good boy (despite his irrepressible enthusiasm for getting in trouble).  He could be loved all day long.  He's never going to be a cat kind of guy.  He's house trained (a huge plus).  And he's pretty good about getting a bath.  He's very fluffy when he's clean and his white parts glisten.  Smore could stand to gain a pound or 5. Smore's approx. DOB is 11/06/2017 so he's the perfect age to be a great companion for many years.

---------

GENERAL APPLICATION NOTES:

We strongly urge adopters to consider a male canine companion if they already have a female GSP/GWP. We get asked several times a year to take in one member of a 2-female GSP family because there are control issues between their girls that result in pretty ferocious fights. Interestingly that never happens among males. Go figure.

Dogs under 2 years of age need to go to a home with another well-socialized canine companion of a similar size (when grown) and within a few years of the pup’s age. This is how they maintain and continue their learning/socialization process. Socialization outside the home is important but doesn’t replace the in-home learning that is so important as the pup ages. https://www.facebook.com/ UtahsPerfectPointers/posts/ 1460968517254816

Most older dogs aren’t interested in having a puppy incessantly chewing on it and demanding attention. If you live outside of the Salt Lake area and are sure that your older dog just loves puppies, please arrange a visit at your home with a 2-4 month old pup for a couple of hours and make sure that your older dog feels the same way about this that you do. Please video the interactions and send it to us.

Just a word of caution........ most pointer types need jobs. Otherwise they're not good pets. They need to be able to utilize their brains and no amount of exercise without a "work" or "thinking" component is adequate. The job doesn't need to be hunting. But it does need to be something that satisfies their genetic predispositions - nose work, agility, tracking, dock diving, etc. The job cannot just be obedience. If they can't use their innate senses they're just never going to be the dog you want for the next 15 years.

A physical fence is required for most of our dogs.

As far as other breeds go, the pointers are generally good with most other breeds with the exception of the Arctic breeds and bulldogs. I'm not sure why, but if there's ever an altercation in daycare between a UPP dog and another dog, it's generally one of those two breeds. It may be the difference in energy levels. It may be some ancient behavior we know nothing about...... Not sure.

Utah's Perfect Pointers is a very small rescue group and doesn't have the resources to adopt to states except for the ones noted above. If you are interested in adopting a GSP please contact the closest groups below. Keep in mind that not all of their dogs may be listed on their sites.

All pets adopted from the center come with a one month free pet insurance which will help to ensure their health and well-being. 
The animal center does its best to help assure that the adopting person and or family finds a pet suitable and compatable for your lifestyle.  
Purebred canine adoption fee is $125.  Puppies up to 4 months $125.  Dogs over 4 months $100.  Some of our canine friends have been sponsored by generous patrons- this allows the adoption fee to be reduced from original fee minus sponsorship amount to good homes.

animal.description:
Our adoption area is limited to UT, NV, ID, OR, WA and MT with a home visit. If you are outside of this area please do a search for your local GSP/GWP/Pointer rescue group.

--------

I'm AMAR! I got my name because I'm a little lover.  I became a "perfect pointer" in Dec. 2020 because the shelter was concerned at how thin and I was.  They think I'm 1/2 labrador retriever and 1/2 GSP.  I was pretty overwhelmed when I got to Casa UPP and spent a lot of time in my crate because I just didn't know how to interact with the other dogs and cats.  After a couple of days Rescue Lady put a muzzle on me and tossed me outside with the herd.  I tried to chomp on a couple of them but they didn't even notice and continued playing.   After a couple of days I decided to join them and the muzzle came off.

Then, wouldn't you know it, my left front paw started to swell up.  My vet thought it might be a foxtail, so tried to flush the wound but didn't find anything.  I'm on antibiotics to see if it might just be a deep-seated infection.  And...... after 2 months I finally get to go to daycare and get some new experiences with all kinds of other dogs and people!

I've turned into a lovely boy.  I'm going to be on the timid side for awhile but I love being with my people and other dogs (and even cats).  I'm ready for a home of my very own!

My approx. DOB is 12/02/2019 so I'm the perfect age to be a great companion for many years.  I'm about 25" at my withers.  I was only 38 lbs when I got to Casa UPP but I'm a perfect 54 lbs now.  I'm still lanky, like most big kids.  My coat glistens and is so soft.

I'd like at least one friendly, well-socialized dog in my new home to interact with and show me the ropes.

Tulip is the more timid of the two and will need a little extra love. She doesn't know what to do when a leash is attached to her collar but we are working on that. Tulip is available for foster-to-adopt as well.

They are currently be boarded in Lewis Center while they learn to love their new comforts--blankets and warmth. Apply to adopt one (or both) of these sweet girls or schedule a visit.

animal.description:
The name is Zelda! I’m a 10 month old lab or maybe shepherd mix, who has been through something traumatic. I can’t tell you what, but it made me very defensive with other dogs. I’m manageable, when walking past but prefer they be at a distance. I am crazy smart and very treat motivated. I can run on the treadmill and will NEED a very active family. While I love kids, I want them to be where I want them to be, so older kids are probably best. Toys are my fav. I will entertain myself or would love for you to throw them for me. I would love a family who can work on my socializing and help me run out my energy. Could you be it? 

Adoption fee: $200

For an application to adopt this pet, please visit our website! www.heavenafterhellrescue.org 
Once approved to adopt, the adoption fee can be paid in cash or check.
 
Adoption includes:
 
Spay or neuter
Heartworm test
Age appropriate vaccines
Rabies
Bordetella
Age appropriate wormer
Flea Preventative
Heartworm preventative
Microchip w/registration
 
We cannot hold animals more than 7 days after we receive a deposit as we don't want them to miss out on a forever home.
Adopters are required to come to us to meet the pets. We cannot ship or transport animals.

animal.description:
Mitch is a sweet-tempered 12 yr old, 10 lb Chihuahua boy who loves to be around his people.  He is happiest when curled up in a lap or snuggled close under the covers.  Mitch is a quiet dog who gets along well with people and other dogs.  He doesn’t hear well and needs a little extra effort to get his attention to go outside and he loves to be outside exploring in the sunshine.  He is 90% house trained and does best when he has access to the outdoors every 2 or 3 hours. 





Our adoption fee of $125.00 helps cover expenses (vaccinations, microchips, spay/neuter, food, housing) for the homeless pets we rescue.  UAF does NOT ship or adopt our adoptables out of state (Arizona) and to ensure the best fit, UAF conducts a home visit to meet other pets and verify a safe, secure yard.

To start the process of adopting this dog or any other dog, please fill out our matchmaking form which can be accessed by copying the following address and pasting it into your browser.  Filling out this form does not obligate you to adopt.

animal.description:
How would you like to spend your golden years away from the only home or family you've ever known? That's exactly what's happened to Boss, a really sweet dog who was brought to the shelter by his family Jan. 21 because they believed he was too old, at age 11, and didn't want to take care of him anymore. The family adopted him as a puppy and taught him well -- he knows sit, stay and lay down and probably more. His family said he is house-trained and good with kids. He's a great old boy who aims to please and is in good shape for his age, except perhaps a bit chubby at 56 pounds. Boss has not been neutered and because of his age, that procedure cannot be done at the shelter. He is up-to-date on vaccinations, heartworm tested negative and will be microchipped upon adoption. Come meet him in Run 77 using ID#626969.

Please note, all of the pet listings on Friends of Shelter Animals for Cobb are done by volunteers, not shelter staff. If this pet came in as lost (not an owner surrender), we don't know how they might be with children, other pets, or if house trained. You can bring your pet to the shelter for a meet & greet with your potential new best friend. When calling the shelter about a cat or dog, please use THE ID NUMBER, names are oftentimes made up by volunteers. 

This pet and many others are available for adoption from the Cobb County Animal Shelter 1060 Al Bishop Dr. Marietta, GA 30008, call (770) 499-4136 for more information. Shelter hours are: Tues. - Sun. 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. by appointment only until further notice, CLOSED Mondays & Holidays.

animal.description: Bonsai is a bouncy young pup with lots of energy! He enjoys tug toys like ropes and will prance proudly through the yard once he finds one. His special favorite toy is the sugar plum fairy plushie, but he is beginning to enjoy a good game of soccer as well! At his age, Bonsai still has some learning to do about manners and is working on more polite ways to get your attention rather than jumping up or nibbling on your sleeve. H has improved quite a bit in his time here, but he has plenty left to learn as well. Sometimes he gets a little nervous with all the strange masks and hats people are wearing these days, but he quickly warms up, especially for a toy or treat. Bonsai currently knows how to sit, lie down, and come when called. He is also working on stay and putting on his harness. We would not recommend a home with small children due to Bonsai's mouthing behaviors. Bonsai would also require a home without cats, as he has a high prey drive. He has participated in our playgroup program and seems to struggle to interact appropriately with other dogs, so we would recommend him as a single dog. He is sure to be plenty of love and energy all on his own!

Mighty Rebel is a big goofy boy - energetic and curious - all wrapped up in a friendly 60 lb. package. Just 1-year-old, Rebel will need your assistance and attention in learning some manners and basic commands. Rebel is a cuddly fella who enjoys snuggling and playing tug. He is a rockstar in our shelter playgroups and has done great with the dogs in his foster home, he is a rough and rowdy player! Rebel is a mixed breed that will do best in a home with children over 12 years of age. Won't you apply for this sweet fella? Adoption questionnaires are processed in the order in which they're received. All of our dogs and puppies go home spayed/neutered, microchipped, heartworm tested (if at least 7 months old), and up to date on age-appropriate vaccinations. We do our best to update information on adoptable pets as frequently as we can. If you're interested in a specific pet, we recommend that you call the shelter and ask if he or she still is available.
For current adoption fees, please see our website, www.dearbornanimals.org. Adoption fee includes: age-appropriate vaccinations, spay or neuter, microchip, ID tag, fecal / worming, basic physical and behavior assessment. Dogs (6 months and older) receive an occult heartworm test. For an additional $20, cats (12 weeks and older) can be tested for FIV (feline immunodeficiency virus) / FLV (feline leukemia).

animal.description:
Please note: We are a small rescue and do not have the resources to respond to inquiries. If a dog is on our website, it is still available. We can not arrange meet & greet without an application. This is a courtesy post for Oakland shelter but you can fill out a foster form at calpaws.org

Adoption fees: $450 for dogs 12 months/younger, $400 for dogs 1-2 Yrs,
$350 for dogs 3-5yrs, and $300 for 6yrs and older

Rocky officially became part of our rescue. 5 years old and brought to the Oakland animal Shelter after his family was no longer able to care for him.

Rocky has a medical condition. He was diagnosed with Perianal Fistulas. This condition can be very painful for a dog.

Rocky is going to require a game plan.

Starting with regulating him with medication along with a perfect diet. Rocky is not stable yet, but we are hoping by having him be in a foster home, he will be able to get the medical care and attention he needs in order to thrive.

This is going to be a long slow road starting with setting him up with a vet that is familiar with perianal fistulas and can help with a direction.

If you would like to donate to Rockys care we would really appreciate it and it would go to a good cause.

Rocky is not yet available for adoption but please donate.
 

You can visit calpaws.org and press the donate button.

Rocky and Cal Paws would like to thanks you for your support.

animal.description:
Breed: Mixed Breed; Lab mix?
Sex: Spayed Female
DOB: ~12/04/2017
Weight: 44 lbs
Energy Level: Medium
Personality Type: Shy, Curious, Food-Motivated! 
History: Transferred from another shelter
Good With: Dogs
Ideal Home: Calm home willing to work with a timid dog. No apartments.
Fence Requirements: Preferred, not required.
Special Info:

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
This is fun loving Dante/ Quincy. He is a terrier mix, abt 2-3 yrs old, gets along well with other dogs & loves to play & cuddle. He is not quick to trust people and takes a little patience and time to get to know. He is very protective of his family & house and does not take to strangers ready, so it is important that his adoptive family work with him and understand his anxiety, quirks and signals. He needs to be with adults that will be patient & kind to earn his trust. Once he trusts you, he will be your best buddy. We recommend he go to a family without small children and one that is a little more dog experienced to help him with his trust & anxiety issues. It would be best to have a fence since he doesn't like strangers. He is a great dog, but not one to be instantly your best friend. As his foster, I can say he is worth your patience. He is fully vetted, neutered, and microchipped. 

All dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations, heartworm tested negative (age 7 months and older) and microchipped. We do not ship or transport. A dog's adoption donation is $200. There is a $5 fee for credit/debit cards.

If you are interested in adopting one of our dogs, please fill out an online application here: www.heartlandsmallanimalrescue.org/canine-application.html

animal.description: When you're this good looking, it's not surprising that everyone thinks you have a future as a supermodel! In addition to his dashing good looks, Ozark has all the qualities of a sophisticated and distinguished gentleman. Not only is he gorgeous, he is also a friendly, curious, and resilient boy and ready to start the next chapter of his life in his forever home. Ozark can be a little shy meeting new people, and prefers that his new friends take things slowly, but earning his trust is worth the effort! He is sweet, loyal, and happy to see his regular volunteer and staff friends during his daily outings at APA!. If you're looking for a walking companion, Ozark would be the perfect buddy - he loves getting outside, taking easy-paced strolls with plenty of stops to sniff all the things. He's not in a rush, and just wants to enjoy the moment and explore his surroundings. On a recent sleepover with a staff member, Ozark was noted to be a quiet, well-mannered house guest and enjoyed looking out the window and watching all the activity going on outside. He also likes riding in the car playing with toys! He's really just a sweet senior guy that is hoping to find a low-key home with a nice adult or two to enjoy his golden years. If you're looking for a companion who is both ready for adventures and for relaxing at home, ask about Ozark today!
